ta bị dính liền ngay vào cây tre, không làm sao gỡ ra được. Ông thông gia thấy vậy chạy đến, định gỡ cho, nó lại đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì cả ông cũng bị dính theo luôn, không lôi ra được nữa.\r\n\r\nHai họ thấy thế không còn ai dám lại gần nó nữa. Còn hai ông kia không còn biết làm thế nào đành van lạy xin nó thả ra cho. Ông chủ hứa gả con gái cho nó, ông thông gia xin về nhà ngay, nó để cho cả hai thề một hồi rồi nó mới đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” thì hai ông rời ngay cây tre, và cây tre cũng rời ra trăm khúc.', '<p>The provided text embodies a traditional folktale that conveys moral lessons about deception, labor, and justice while reflecting characteristics intrinsic to folk literature, such as simplicity in narrative, engagement with supernatural elements, and a certain ironic humor. Through a careful analysis of the work, we can unpack several dimensions, including the main ideas, structure, tone, language, and underlying themes.</p>\n<h3>Main Ideas and Underlying Meanings</h3>\n<p>At the core of this narrative lies the theme of exploitation versus justice. The old man utilizes the labor of the servant, promising him the reward of marrying his daughter, only to renege on his promise once the servant has worked hard and diligently over three years. This premise raises critical questions about trust, integrity, and the often unequal power dynamics in human relationships. The servant, however, represents resilience and perseverance despite his poverty and lack of agency.</p>\n<p>When presented with a seemingly impossible task—finding a bamboo with a hundred nodes—the servant could embody the hope that ascribes deeper significance to toil and unwavering commitment. Following the guidance of the old man with a white beard, who represents wisdom and supernatural assistance, the servant’s successful retrieval of the bamboo exemplifies that faith and hard work can yield unexpected rewards.</p>\n<h3>Structure and Flow</h3>\n<p>The text is structured in a linear progression, typical of folk narratives. It begins with the introduction of characters and the initial dilemma— the promise made to the servant. Following this, the tale builds tension as the servant is tasked with the impossible quest while silently struggling against the unfairness of the situation. The narrative peaks when the servant applies his newfound power to turn the tables on his master and the suitor, achieving a form of poetic justice. The resolution follows, where the master must fulfill his promise, thereby restoring equilibrium.</p>\n<p>Each segment of the story is tightly linked to the central conflict, ensuring a cohesive flow that maintains the reader\'s engagement. The gradual unveiling of events—from the promise to the betrayal and eventual triumph—labels the tale as one of transformation.</p>\n<h3>Tone and Style</h3>\n<p>The tone of the narrative reflects both humor and a serious undertone. The comical elements arise from the absurdity of the task assigned to the servant and the eventual fate of the master and suitor being stuck to the bamboo. This creates a light-hearted yet critical exploration of human folly. The style is straightforward yet vivid, employing a descriptive approach that invites readers into the world of the characters. Phrases like &quot;cầm gậy trúc&quot; (holding a bamboo stick) paint a clear picture while rooting the story in an identifiable culture.</p>\n<h3>Language and Word Choice</h3>\n<p>The language used throughout the narrative is simple but enriched with cultural references and idiomatic expressions. Repeated incantations such as “Khắc nhập, khắc xuất” emphasize a rhythmic quality reminiscent of incantations or magical spells often found in folklore. The fusion of standard language with folkloric charm enriches the storytelling, allowing the moral lessons to be absorbed with impact.</p>\n<p>The use of dialogue further enhances the characters\' personalities; the old man is wise and enigmatic, whereas the master is portrayed as greedy and deceptive, a classic characterization seen in folktales where archetypes play crucial roles. Word choices such as &quot;lừa,&quot; meaning deceit, resonate deeply with the overarching theme of betrayal and manipulation.</p>\n<h3>Sentence Patterns and Grammatical Techniques</h3>\n<p>The use of direct speech in dialogues, alongside third-person narration, provides a dynamic interplay between character motivations and narrative progression. The blend of short, punchy sentences—especially during the climactic resolution—intensifies the action and heightens the dramatic tension. There are instances of repetition for emphasis, particularly in the magical chants, which not only serve a narrative purpose but also engage readers in the rhythm of the text.</p>\n<h3>Subtle Themes and Nuances</h3>\n<p>Several subtle undercurrents can be observed. For instance, the reliance on elders and mentors in the form of the wise old man indicates a cultural appreciation for wisdom and guidance. Moreover, the aspect of having the characters bound to the bamboo symbolizes the consequences of their actions—one cannot escape the implications of deceit. The text also reflects on class struggles, with the servant representing the oppressed who, through cleverness and perseverance, is able to upend the expectations of societal hierarchy.</p>\n<p>In sum, this narrative encapsulates universal themes of justice and morality woven within the fabric of traditional storytelling. Through an intricate characterization, humor interlaced with gravity, and profound moral allegories, it resembles many classic tales that caution against greed and validate the virtues of hard work and integrity. The richness in language and construction serves to engage the reader while delivering a timeless lesson that resonates across cultures and eras.</p>', 'text analysis', '', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750f9e75e1782.72458795', '2024-12-04 17:55:03', '2024-12-04 17:55:03'),
(99, 9, 'Ngày xưa, có một ông già nhà quê có một cô gái đẹp. Trong nhà phải thuê một đầy tớ trai, ông ta muốn lợi dụng nó làm việc khỏi trả tiền, mới bảo nó rằng: “Mày chịu khó làm ăn với tao rồi tao gả con gái cho”. Người ở mừng lắm, ra sức làm lụng tới khuya không nề hà mệt nhọc. Nó giúp việc được ba năm, nhà ông ta mỗi ngày một giàu có.\r\n\r\nÔng nhà giàu không còn nghĩ đến lời hứa cũ nữa, đem con gái gả cho con một nhà phú hộ khác ở trong làng.\r\n\r\nSáng hôm sắp đưa dâu, ông chủ gọi đứa ở lên lừa nó một lần nữa, bảo rằng: “Bây giờ mày lên rừng tìm cho ra một cây tre có trăm đốt đem về đây làm đũa ăn cưới, thì tao cho mày lấy con gái tao ngay”.\r\n\r\nĐứa ở tưởng thật, vác dao đi rừng. Nó kiếm khắp nơi, hết rừng này qua rừng nọ, không tìm đâu thấy có cây tre đủ trăm đốt. Buồn khổ quá, nó ngồi một chỗ ôm mặt khóc. Bỗng thấy có một ông lão râu tóc bạc phơ, tay cầm gậy trúc hiện ra bảo nó: “Tại sao con khóc, hãy nói ta nghe, ta sẽ giúp cho”. Nó bèn đem đầu đuôi câu chuyện ông phú hộ hứa gả con gái cho mà kể lại. Ông lão nghe xong, mới bảo rằng: “Con đi chặt đếm đủ trăm cái đốt tre rồi đem lại đây ta bảo”.\r\n\r\nNó làm theo y lời dặn, ông dạy nó đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” (vào ngay, vào ngay) đủ ba lần, thì một trăm khúc tre tự nhiên dính lại với nhau thành một cây trẻ đủ một trăm đốt. Nó mừng quá, định vác về, nhưng cây tre dài quá, vướng không đi được. Ông lão bảo nó đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” (ra ngay, ra ngay) đúng ba lần thì cây tre trăm đốt lại rời ra ngay từng khúc.\r\n\r\nNó bèn bó cả lại mà gánh về nhà. Đến nơi thấy hai họ đang ăn uống vui vẻ, sắp đến lúc rước dâu, nó mới hay là ông chủ đã lừa nó đem gả con gái cho người ta rồi. Nó không nói gì, đợi lúc nhà trai đốt pháo cưới, bèn đem một trăm khúc tre xếp dài dưới đất, rồi lẩm bẩm đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” cho liền lại thành một cây tre trăm đốt, đoạn gọi ông chủ đến bảo là đã tìm ra được, và đòi gả con gái cho nó. Ông chủ lấy làm lạ cầm cây tre lên xem, nó đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì ông ta bị dính liền ngay vào cây tre, không làm sao gỡ ra được. Ông thông gia thấy vậy chạy đến, định gỡ cho, nó lại đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì cả ông cũng bị dính theo luôn, không lôi ra được nữa.\r\n\r\nHai họ thấy thế không còn ai dám lại gần nó nữa. Còn hai ông kia không còn biết làm thế nào đành van lạy xin nó thả ra cho. Ông chủ hứa gả con gái cho nó, ông thông gia xin về nhà ngay, nó để cho cả hai thề một hồi rồi nó mới đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” thì hai ông rời ngay cây tre, và cây tre cũng rời ra trăm khúc.', '<p>The provided text is a folktale rich with moral lessons, cultural nuances, and deep underlying themes that can be analyzed from various angles. First, let\'s explore the main ideas and meanings encapsulated within the narrative.</p>\n<h3>Main Ideas and Underlying Meanings</h3>\n<p>At the heart of the folktale lies the theme of deception and exploitation, primarily embodied in the character of the old farmer. The farmer initially makes a promise, offering his daughter in marriage to the servant in exchange for labor without compensation. This aspect of exploitation exemplifies a common trope in folktales where those in positions of power manipulate those who are vulnerable. The servant\'s unwavering dedication despite the lack of fair compensation presents a critique of blind loyalty and the pitfalls of naivety.</p>\n<p>Additionally, the tale grapples with themes of justice and retribution. The servant\'s resourcefulness becomes pivotal when faced with betrayal. The introduction of the old man who aids the servant signifies the presence of wisdom and possibly supernatural help within the narrative—elements that are consistently prevalent in folklore. The servant\'s eventual success not only provides a resolution to his plight but serves as an all-encompassing reclaiming of power, suggesting that through cleverness and determination, justice can be served.</p>\n<h3>Structure and Flow</h3>\n<p>The narrative follows a clear chronological structure, beginning with the servant’s initial promise of marriage, followed by the betrayal, and concluding with the servant’s clever resolution to the situation. Each segment progresses logically, building tension as the servant endeavors to fulfill the impossible task assigned by the farmer. This task and the ensuing journey create an emotional crescendo that peaks as the servant devises his plan against the farmer.</p>\n<p>The organization of the folktale reflects the cyclical nature of folklore, where motifs of deceit lead to moments of enlightenment and justice. Each paragraph contributes meaningfully to the development of the principal character—the servant. The climax occurs at the wedding, where the servant\'s cleverness transforms the celebration into a moment of justice against those who undermined him.</p>\n<h3>Tone and Style</h3>\n<p>The tone of the text oscillates between serious and subtly humorous. The seriousness arises from the exploration of manipulation and betrayal, prompting the reader to reflect on the moral implications of the characters\' actions. Conversely, the humorous element emerges when the farmer and the prospective in-law become ensnared by their own machinations. This duality imbues the story with a sense of lighthearted irony, effectively engaging the reader while prompting consideration of moral lessons.</p>\n<p>The style reflects traditional storytelling, rich with idiomatic expressions and a somewhat archaic, yet engaging linguistic form. The use of repetitive phrases like “Khắc nhập, khắc xuất” not only serves functional purposes within the narrative (transforming the bamboo) but also enhances the oral quality of the tale. Such repetition signifies cultural motifs common in oral traditions—providing rhythm, aiding memorization, and emphasizing the magic inherent in the story.</p>\n<h3>Language Usage and Diction</h3>\n<p>The choice of words in the text is deliberately simple yet evocative, making the tale accessible while also encapsulating cultural elements. Terms like “tre” (bamboo) and “đũa” (chopsticks) are significant within Vietnamese culture and serve to ground the story in its local context. Additionally, the diction reflects the socio-economic disparities, with terms that denote wealth (&quot;nhà phú hộ&quot;) juxtaposed against more humble origins (&quot;người ở&quot;). This contrast paints a vivid picture of class dynamics and reinforces the exploitative relationship between the farmer and the servant.</p>\n<p>The portrayal of characters also exemplifies vivid dichotomies. The old farmer embodies greed and deceit, while the figure of the old man represents wisdom and guidance. This dichotomy encourages readers to engage with the narrative as a moral lesson on the virtues of honesty and cleverness versus deceit and greed.</p>\n<h3>Sentence Patterns and Grammatical Techniques</h3>\n<p>The sentences predominantly reflect a storytelling cadence, featuring straightforward structures that enhance clarity. However, moments of complexity arise during the incantations, where repetition and specific phrasing create a sense of ritual and the supernatural. These instances not only contribute to the thematic depth but also highlight the magical realism characteristic of many folktales. </p>\n<p>Analyzing the grammatical choices, the employment of the conditional &quot;nếu&quot; (if) surfaces crucial possibilities and future implications, reinforcing the tale’s moral contingencies based on the characters\' actions. The interplay of direct speech and narration captures the dialogue\'s immediacy, making the emotional stakes more palpable.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>In summation, this folktale intricately weaves together themes of exploitation, justice, and clever resolution, underpinned by cultural moralities. The organization and unifying elements of the narrative work cohesively, leading readers from betrayal through struggle to resolution. The tone blends seriousness with humor, reflecting on human nature through vivid character portrayals. The language choice and sentence structures deepen the reader\'s connection to folklore while emphasizing essential life lessons. Thus, this folktale not only entertains but serves as a timeless reminder of the complexities of morality and human relationships.</p>', 'text analysis', '', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750fa6c3541f1.24511019', '2024-12-04 17:57:16', '2024-12-04 17:57:16'),
(100, 9, 'Ngày xưa, có một ông già nhà quê có một cô gái đẹp. Trong nhà phải thuê một đầy tớ trai, ông ta muốn lợi dụng nó làm việc khỏi trả tiền, mới bảo nó rằng: “Mày chịu khó làm ăn với tao rồi tao gả con gái cho”. Người ở mừng lắm, ra sức làm lụng tới khuya không nề hà mệt nhọc. Nó giúp việc được ba năm, nhà ông ta mỗi ngày một giàu có.\r\n\r\nÔng nhà giàu không còn nghĩ đến lời hứa cũ nữa, đem con gái gả cho con một nhà phú hộ khác ở trong làng.\r\n\r\nSáng hôm sắp đưa dâu, ông chủ gọi đứa ở lên lừa nó một lần nữa, bảo rằng: “Bây giờ mày lên rừng tìm cho ra một cây tre có trăm đốt đem về đây làm đũa ăn cưới, thì tao cho mày lấy con gái tao ngay”.\r\n\r\nĐứa ở tưởng thật, vác dao đi rừng. Nó kiếm khắp nơi, hết rừng này qua rừng nọ, không tìm đâu thấy có cây tre đủ trăm đốt. Buồn khổ quá, nó ngồi một chỗ ôm mặt khóc. Bỗng thấy có một ông lão râu tóc bạc phơ, tay cầm gậy trúc hiện ra bảo nó: “Tại sao con khóc, hãy nói ta nghe, ta sẽ giúp cho”. Nó bèn đem đầu đuôi câu chuyện ông phú hộ hứa gả con gái cho mà kể lại. Ông lão nghe xong, mới bảo rằng: “Con đi chặt đếm đủ trăm cái đốt tre rồi đem lại đây ta bảo”.\r\n\r\nNó làm theo y lời dặn, ông dạy nó đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” (vào ngay, vào ngay) đủ ba lần, thì một trăm khúc tre tự nhiên dính lại với nhau thành một cây trẻ đủ một trăm đốt. Nó mừng quá, định vác về, nhưng cây tre dài quá, vướng không đi được. Ông lão bảo nó đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” (ra ngay, ra ngay) đúng ba lần thì cây tre trăm đốt lại rời ra ngay từng khúc.\r\n\r\nNó bèn bó cả lại mà gánh về nhà. Đến nơi thấy hai họ đang ăn uống vui vẻ, sắp đến lúc rước dâu, nó mới hay là ông chủ đã lừa nó đem gả con gái cho người ta rồi. Nó không nói gì, đợi lúc nhà trai đốt pháo cưới, bèn đem một trăm khúc tre xếp dài dưới đất, rồi lẩm bẩm đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” cho liền lại thành một cây tre trăm đốt, đoạn gọi ông chủ đến bảo là đã tìm ra được, và đòi gả con gái cho nó. Ông chủ lấy làm lạ cầm cây tre lên xem, nó đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì ông ta bị dính liền ngay vào cây tre, không làm sao gỡ ra được. Ông thông gia thấy vậy chạy đến, định gỡ cho, nó lại đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì cả ông cũng bị dính theo luôn, không lôi ra được nữa.\r\n\r\nHai họ thấy thế không còn ai dám lại gần nó nữa. Còn hai ông kia không còn biết làm thế nào đành van lạy xin nó thả ra cho. Ông chủ hứa gả con gái cho nó, ông thông gia xin về nhà ngay, nó để cho cả hai thề một hồi rồi nó mới đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” thì hai ông rời ngay cây tre, và cây tre cũng rời ra trăm khúc.', '<p>This text is a rich, folkloric narrative embedded with classic themes of deception, exploitation, and justice. It unfolds a cautionary tale that explores the moral hinterlands of rural life, where power dynamics and social hierarchies shape individuals\' fates. Below, I will offer a comprehensive analysis of the text across various dimensions.</p>\n<h3>Main Ideas and Underlying Meanings</h3>\n<p>The central plot revolves around an old farmer who exploits a servant for his own gain. His promise of marrying his daughter to the servant becomes a deceptive tool to manipulate labor. This setup establishes an initial power imbalance, reflecting the socio-economic relationships prevalent in agrarian societies. The servant\'s relentless labor signifies his hope and determination, which speaks to broader themes of aspiration and the pitfalls of misplaced trust.</p>\n<p>The turning point arises when the servant confronts the old man’s betrayal. The servant’s quest for a bamboo pole with a hundred segments symbolizes the absurdity required to fulfill the old man\'s unreasonable demands. This quest sets the stage for an encounter with a wise, magical elder who offers a solution—indicative of the folkloric tradition where supernatural aid provides resolution and justice.</p>\n<h3>Organizational Structure and Cohesion</h3>\n<p>The narrative is structured sequentially, moving from the servant’s initial employment to his relentless search for the bamboo, leading up to the climax of revenge through magical intervention. Each section logically flows into the next: from the initial setup of deceit, to the protagonist\'s emotional turmoil, and ultimately to the resolution where the servant gains control. The transitions maintain tension and engagement, culminating effectively in a climax that showcases justice being served.</p>\n<h3>Tone and Style</h3>\n<p>The tone of the narrative is folktale-like, combining elements of humor, moralism, and a sense of wonder. The simplicity of the language reflects the rural setting and the characters\' social status, allowing readers to easily immerse themselves in the story. The use of magical realism, with the appearance of the old man who assists the servant, adds a layer of enchantment, typical of fairy tales, promoting themes of virtue rewarded and misdeeds punished.</p>\n<h3>Language Usage and Diction</h3>\n<p>The language employed is straightforward yet vivid, comprising simple diction that lends accessibility while retaining a sense of cultural specificity. The use of repetitions in phrases like &quot;Khắc nhập, khắc xuất&quot; not only emphasizes magical incantations but also serves as a narrative device to build anticipation. These phrases are pivotal, layering the text with a charm that enhances its rhythmic quality.</p>\n<p>Imagery plays an important role; the notion of a bamboo pole of one hundred segments evokes a visual tableau that symbolizes perseverance, unattainable goals, and ultimately, transformation. The contrasting images of labor (the servant’s hard work) versus the calmness of the wedding festivities heighten the emotional stakes.</p>\n<h3>Sentence Structure and Grammatical Techniques</h3>\n<p>The text generally employs simple, declarative sentences, which mirror the oral storytelling tradition. Occasional use of longer sentences conveys the urgency of the servant\'s plight or the complexities of the magical events. This variation in sentence length allows for a dynamic reading experience.</p>\n<p>The narrative also uses direct dialogue effectively to develop character and move the plot forward. The characters’ speech patterns are reflective of their status— the rich man\'s authoritative commands starkly contrast the servant\'s desperate pleas, enhancing the socio-economic commentary inherent in the story.</p>\n<h3>Themes and Nuances</h3>\n<p>Subtle themes of justice and comeuppance permeate the story, highlighting how the oppressed can rise against the oppressor through cleverness and persistence. The servant’s eventual triumph also suggests an implicit critique of social hierarchies, as his resourcefulness disrupts the established order. Additionally, the magical elder’s role signifies the belief in higher justice that transcends human folly, insinuating a protective cosmic order that rewards integrity and punishes deceit.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>In summary, the narrative encapsulates a microcosm of societal dynamics through a folkloric lens, weaving the elements of deception, aspiration, and eventual justice into a compelling tale. The structure, tone, style, and use of language work cohesively to convey deep moral lessons, transforming a simple story into a rich tapestry reflecting human experience. This complexity underscores the timeless nature of folktales, which serve not merely as entertainment but as vehicles for cultural wisdom and ethical reflections.</p>', 'text analysis', '', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750fd24602ff1.07784950', '2024-12-04 18:08:52', '2024-12-04 18:08:52');
INSERT INTO `text_analysis` (`id`, `user_id`, `text_content`, `analysis_result`, `type_of_analysis`, `evaluation`, `status`, `analysis_evaluation_code`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(101, 9, 'Ngày xưa, có một ông già nhà quê có một cô gái đẹp. Trong nhà phải thuê một đầy tớ trai, ông ta muốn lợi dụng nó làm việc khỏi trả tiền, mới bảo nó rằng: “Mày chịu khó làm ăn với tao rồi tao gả con gái cho”. Người ở mừng lắm, ra sức làm lụng tới khuya không nề hà mệt nhọc. Nó giúp việc được ba năm, nhà ông ta mỗi ngày một giàu có.\r\n\r\nÔng nhà giàu không còn nghĩ đến lời hứa cũ nữa, đem con gái gả cho con một nhà phú hộ khác ở trong làng.\r\n\r\nSáng hôm sắp đưa dâu, ông chủ gọi đứa ở lên lừa nó một lần nữa, bảo rằng: “Bây giờ mày lên rừng tìm cho ra một cây tre có trăm đốt đem về đây làm đũa ăn cưới, thì tao cho mày lấy con gái tao ngay”.\r\n\r\nĐứa ở tưởng thật, vác dao đi rừng. Nó kiếm khắp nơi, hết rừng này qua rừng nọ, không tìm đâu thấy có cây tre đủ trăm đốt. Buồn khổ quá, nó ngồi một chỗ ôm mặt khóc. Bỗng thấy có một ông lão râu tóc bạc phơ, tay cầm gậy trúc hiện ra bảo nó: “Tại sao con khóc, hãy nói ta nghe, ta sẽ giúp cho”. Nó bèn đem đầu đuôi câu chuyện ông phú hộ hứa gả con gái cho mà kể lại. Ông lão nghe xong, mới bảo rằng: “Con đi chặt đếm đủ trăm cái đốt tre rồi đem lại đây ta bảo”.\r\n\r\nNó làm theo y lời dặn, ông dạy nó đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” (vào ngay, vào ngay) đủ ba lần, thì một trăm khúc tre tự nhiên dính lại với nhau thành một cây trẻ đủ một trăm đốt. Nó mừng quá, định vác về, nhưng cây tre dài quá, vướng không đi được. Ông lão bảo nó đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” (ra ngay, ra ngay) đúng ba lần thì cây tre trăm đốt lại rời ra ngay từng khúc.\r\n\r\nNó bèn bó cả lại mà gánh về nhà. Đến nơi thấy hai họ đang ăn uống vui vẻ, sắp đến lúc rước dâu, nó mới hay là ông chủ đã lừa nó đem gả con gái cho người ta rồi. Nó không nói gì, đợi lúc nhà trai đốt pháo cưới, bèn đem một trăm khúc tre xếp dài dưới đất, rồi lẩm bẩm đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” cho liền lại thành một cây tre trăm đốt, đoạn gọi ông chủ đến bảo là đã tìm ra được, và đòi gả con gái cho nó. Ông chủ lấy làm lạ cầm cây tre lên xem, nó đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì ông ta bị dính liền ngay vào cây tre, không làm sao gỡ ra được. Ông thông gia thấy vậy chạy đến, định gỡ cho, nó lại đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì cả ông cũng bị dính theo luôn, không lôi ra được nữa.\r\n\r\nHai họ thấy thế không còn ai dám lại gần nó nữa. Còn hai ông kia không còn biết làm thế nào đành van lạy xin nó thả ra cho. Ông chủ hứa gả con gái cho nó, ông thông gia xin về nhà ngay, nó để cho cả hai thề một hồi rồi nó mới đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” thì hai ông rời ngay cây tre, và cây tre cũng rời ra trăm khúc.', '<p>The provided text is a folktale that encapsulates themes of deceit, justice, and the triumph of the underdog, woven into the fabric of its narrative. It is rich in illustrative details, cultural nuances, and moral undertones, contributing to a multifaceted reading experience. Let’s delve into a comprehensive analysis of its major ideas, structure, tone, language usage, and underlying messages.</p>\n<p><strong>Main Ideas and Underlying Meanings:</strong></p>\n<p>At its core, the tale addresses the concepts of exploitation and justice through the character of the young servant and the greedy landlord. The initial promise made by the landlord to marry off his daughter to the worker for his efforts highlights the theme of manipulation. The servant\'s hard work is juxtaposed with the landlord\'s eventual betrayal, underscoring an important moral lesson about the consequences of dishonesty.</p>\n<p>The arrival of the elderly man with the magical solution serves as a pivotal turning point in the plot. This character introduces a supernatural element that reflects the belief in wisdom and assistance coming from unexpected sources. The repetition of commands (&quot;Khắc nhập, khắc xuất&quot;) symbolizes the use of knowledge and cleverness as a means of rectifying wrongs. The tale subtly suggests that justice is attainable, albeit sometimes through unconventional means, thereby resonating with the notion of karmic balance.</p>\n<p><strong>Organization and Flow:</strong></p>\n<p>The narrative is structured in a cohesive manner that enhances its readability. The story unfolds chronologically, beginning with the introduction of the characters and their relationships. Each paragraph builds upon the last, creating a rhythmic flow that guides the reader through the servant’s trial, the landlord’s deceit, the magical intervention, and finally the resolution where justice is served.</p>\n<p>For instance, the initial setup of the landlord’s promise sets the stage for the ensuing conflict. The lamentation of the servant when he is tricked serves as a poignant moment that elicits empathy. The magical resolution introduces an unexpected twist, transforming a seemingly linear narrative into a complex interaction between fate and agency.</p>\n<p><strong>Tone and Style:</strong></p>\n<p>The tone is a blend of whimsicality and seriousness, characteristic of folk narratives. While the overall language is simple and accessible, allowing for a broad audience appeal, it carries an element of playfulness, especially through the use of magical commands and the antics surrounding the transformation of bamboo. This duality reflects the folk tradition’s purpose of both entertaining and educating.</p>\n<p>The use of direct dialogue adds to the immediacy of the tale, drawing readers into the interactions between the characters. Phrases like, “Mày chịu khó làm ăn với tao rồi tao gả con gái cho,” are colloquial and lend authenticity to the characters’ voices, grounding their experiences in a specific cultural context.</p>\n<p><strong>Language Usage and Diction:</strong></p>\n<p>The diction throughout the narrative is strategic; common vernacular is used when conveying the main characters’ speech, enhancing relatability and immersion. For example, the casual language employed by the landlord contrasts starkly with the magical lingo of the elder, emphasizing the divide between the mundane and the extraordinary.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, the specific repetition of terms related to the magical commands (“Khắc nhập,” “Khắc xuất”) creates a rhythmic quality akin to chants or spells, imbuing the text with a folkloric essence. This use of language not only serves as a narrative device but also emphasizes the power of words in shaping reality within the story\'s universe.</p>\n<p><strong>Sentence Patterns and Grammatical Techniques:</strong></p>\n<p>The text employs varied sentence structures, including simple declarative sentences for clarity and more complex sentences to convey nuanced actions and emotions. The storytelling often utilizes cumulative sentences to build tension, notably during the servant\'s desperate search for the bamboo and the climactic moment of his revelation.</p>\n<p>Additionally, the use of imperative sentences during the magical moments invokes an immediacy and encourages reader engagement, making them feel a part of the servant\'s journey toward resolution. The contrast between the informal speech of the characters and the formal language of the elder amplifies the narrative’s tension, reinforcing the thematic dichotomy between exploitation and assistance.</p>\n<p><strong>Multidimensional Analysis:</strong></p>\n<p>Through its rich tapestry of characters and events, this folktale reflects the cultural values of integrity, loyalty, and the idea that wisdom often comes from the unlikeliest of sources. The magical elements serve as metaphors for inner strength and the rewards of perseverance against systemic oppression. Each character plays a vital role in the moral landscape, from the greedy landlord to the wise elder, underscoring the importance of community and mutual respect.</p>\n<p>The psychological journey of the servant—from hopeful worker to heartbroken pawn to cunning victor—mirrors the struggles faced by many in society who confront exploitation. The transformation and resolution bring forth the idea that while wrongdoing may occur, there exists a potential for retribution that can restore balance.</p>\n<p>In conclusion, this folk narrative weaves together timeless themes rooted in cultural belief systems, employing rich language and structural integrity to create a compelling tale that resonates on multiple levels. The interplay between magical realism and moral undertones provides a deeper commentary on human nature, societal norms, and the triumph of good over evil. Each element of the story intricately contributes to a holistic understanding of the journey from victimhood to empowerment, embodying the virtues and wisdom of the cultural heritage from which it springs.</p>', 'text analysis', '', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750fda9f1ce34.02922932', '2024-12-04 18:11:05', '2024-12-04 18:11:05'),
(102, 9, 'Cristiano Ronaldo dos Santos Aveiro GOIH ComM (Portuguese pronunciation: [kɾiʃˈtjɐnu ʁɔˈnaldu] ⓘ; born 5 February 1985) is a Portuguese professional footballer who plays as a forward for and captains both the Saudi Pro League club Al Nassr and the Portugal national team. Widely regarded as one of the greatest players of all time, Ronaldo has won numerous individual accolades throughout his career, such as five Ballon d\'Or awards, a record three UEFA Men\'s Player of the Year Awards, four European Golden Shoes, and was named five times the world\'s best player by FIFA,[note 3] the most by a European player. He has won 33 trophies in his career, including seven league titles, five UEFA Champions Leagues, the UEFA European Championship and the UEFA Nations League. Ronaldo holds the records for most appearances (183), goals (140) and assists (42) in the Champions League, most appearances (30), assists (8), goals in the European Championship (14), international appearances (217) and international goals (135). He is one of the few players to have made over 1,200 professional career appearances, the most by an outfield player, and has scored over 900 official senior career goals for club and country, making him the top goalscorer of all time.[note 4]\r\n\r\nRonaldo began his senior career with Sporting CP, before signing with Manchester United in 2003, winning the FA Cup in his first season. He went on to win three consecutive Premier League titles, the Champions League and the FIFA Club World Cup; at age 23, he won his first Ballon d\'Or. Ronaldo was the subject of the then-most expensive association football transfer when he signed for Real Madrid in 2009 in a transfer worth €94 million (£80 million). He became a key contributor and formed an attacking trio with Karim Benzema and Gareth Bale which was integral to the team winning four Champions Leagues from 2014 to 2018, including La Décima. During this period, he won back-to-back Ballons d\'Or in 2013 and 2014, and again in 2016 and 2017, and was runner-up three times behind Lionel Messi, his perceived career rival. He also became the club\'s all-time top goalscorer and the all-time top scorer in the Champions League, and finished as the competition\'s top scorer for six consecutive seasons between 2012 and 2018. With Real, Ronaldo won four Champions Leagues, two La Liga titles, two Copas del Rey, two UEFA Super Cups and three Club World Cups. In 2018, he signed for Juventus in a transfer worth an initial €100 million (£88 million), the most expensive transfer for an Italian club and for a player over 30 years old. He won two Serie A titles, two Supercoppa Italiana trophies and a Coppa Italia, became the inaugural Serie A Most Valuable Player, and the first footballer to finish as top scorer in the English, Spanish and Italian leagues. He returned to Manchester United in 2021, finishing his only full season as the club\'s top scorer, before his contract was terminated in 2022. In 2023, he signed for Al Nassr.\r\n\r\nRonaldo made his international debut for Portugal in 2003 at the age of 18 and has earned more than 200 caps, making him history\'s most-capped male player.[8] With 130 international goals, he is also the all-time top male goalscorer. Ronaldo has played in eleven major tournaments and scored in ten; he scored his first international goal at Euro 2004, where he helped Portugal reach the final. He assumed captaincy of the national team in July 2008. In 2015, Ronaldo was named the best Portuguese player of all time by the Portuguese Football Federation. The following year, he led Portugal to their first major tournament title at Euro 2016, and received the Silver Boot as the second-highest goalscorer of the tournament. This achievement saw him receive his fourth Ballon d\'Or. He also led them to victory in the inaugural UEFA Nations League in 2019, receiving the top scorer award in the finals, and later received the Golden Boot as top scorer of Euro 2020. The same tournament, he broke the record of most international goals scored in men\'s football and became the player with the most international caps in men\'s football in 2023.\r\n\r\nOne of the world\'s most marketable and famous athletes, Ronaldo was ranked the world\'s highest-paid athlete by Forbes in 2016, 2017, 2023, and 2024 and the world\'s most famous athlete by ESPN from 2016 to 2019. Time included him on their list of the 100 most influential people in the world in 2014. Ronaldo is the most popular sportsperson on social media: he counts over 1 billion total followers across Facebook, Twitter, YouTube and Instagram, making him the first person to achieve that feat. In 2020, Ronaldo was named to the Ballon d\'Or Dream Team and he is the first footballer and the third sportsman to earn US$1 billion in his career.\r\n\r\nEarly life\r\nCristiano Ronaldo dos Santos Aveiro was born on 5 February 1985 in the São Pedro parish of Funchal, the capital of the Portuguese island of Madeira, and grew up in the nearby parish of Santo António.[9][10] He is the fourth and youngest child of Maria Dolores dos Santos Viveiros Aveiro, who worked as a cook in the hospitality industry and a cleaning woman,[11][12] and José Dinis Aveiro, a municipal gardener at the Junta de Freguesia of Santo António and part-time kit man for football club Andorinha.[13][14][15] His great-grandmother on his father\'s side, Isabel da Piedade, an African woman, was born in the island of São Vicente, in what was then Portuguese Cape Verde, and moved to Madeira Island at 16.[16][17] He has one older brother, Hugo, and two older sisters, Elma and Liliana Cátia \"Kátia\".[2] He was named after actor and U.S. President Ronald Reagan, whom his father was a fan of.[18] His mother revealed that she wanted to abort him due to poverty, his father\'s alcoholism, and having too many children already, but her doctor refused to perform the procedure.[19][20] Ronaldo grew up in an impoverished Catholic home, sharing a room with all his siblings.[21]\r\n\r\nAs a child, Ronaldo played for Andorinha from 1992 to 1995,[22] where his father was the kit man,[13] and later spent two years with Nacional. In 1997, aged 12, he went on a three-day trial with Sporting CP, who signed him for a fee of £1,500.[23] He subsequently moved from Madeira to Lisbon to join Sporting CP\'s youth system.[23] By age 14, while struggling with his school duties and responsibilities in Escola EB2 de Telheiras, his school in the Telheiras area of Lisbon, Ronaldo believed he had the ability to play semi-professionally and agreed with his mother and his tutor at Sporting CP, Leonel Pontes,[24] to cease his education to focus entirely on football.[25][26] With a troubled life as a student,[27] and although living in Lisbon area away from his Madeiran family,[28][29] he did not complete schooling beyond the 6th grade.[30][31] While popular with other students at school, he had been expelled after throwing a chair at his teacher, who he said had \"disrespected\" him.[25] One year later, he was diagnosed with tachycardia, a condition that could have forced him to give up playing football.[32] Ronaldo underwent heart surgery where a laser was used to cauterise multiple cardiac pathways into one, altering his resting heart rate.[33] He was discharged from the hospital hours after the procedure and resumed training a few days later.[34] In 2021, Cristiano Ronaldo\'s mother, Dolores Aveiro, stated in an interview for Sporting CP\'s official television channel (Sporting TV) that her son would be a bricklayer if he hadn\'t become a professional football player.[35]\r\n\r\nGrowing up, Ronaldo idolised the Brazilian footballers Ronaldinho and Ronaldo Nazário, and has described them as leaving \"a beautiful history in football\".[36]\r\n\r\nClub career\r\nMain article: Career of Cristiano Ronaldo § Club career\r\nSporting CP (2002–2003)\r\nAfter impressing in Sporting\'s youth teams, he was promoted to the main team by first-team manager László Bölöni. At age 17, on 14 August 2002, he played his first official match for the first team, in a UEFA Champions League qualifying round at José Alvalade Stadium against Inter Milan,[37] and his Primeira Liga debut, took place a month later against Braga, and on 7 October, he scored two goals against Moreirense in their 3–0 win.[38] Over the course of the 2002–03 season, his representatives suggested the player to Liverpool manager Gérard Houllier and Barcelona president Joan Laporta.[39] Manager Arsène Wenger, who was interested in signing Ronaldo, met with him at Arsenal\'s stadium in November to discuss a possible transfer.[40]\r\n\r\nManchester United manager Alex Ferguson was determined to acquire Ronaldo on a permanent move urgently, after Sporting defeated United 3–1 at the inauguration of the Estádio José Alvalade on 6 August 2003. Initially, United had planned to sign Ronaldo and loan him back to Sporting for a year.[41] Having been impressed by him, the United players urged Ferguson to sign him. After the game, Ferguson agreed to pay Sporting £12.24 million[41] for what he considered to be \"one of the most exciting young players\" he had ever seen.[42]\r\n\r\nManchester United (2003–2009)\r\n2003–2007: Development and breakthrough\r\n\"There have been a few players described as \'the new George Best\' over the years, but this is the first time it\'s been a compliment to me.\"\r\n\r\n—Former Manchester United player George Best hails the 18-year-old Cristiano Ronaldo in 2003.[43]\r\nManchester United\'s signed Ronaldo for £12 million on 12 August 2003,[44] an England record for a teenager.[45] This also made him the first Portuguese player to sign for the club.[46]\r\n\r\nAlthough he requested the number 28, his number at Sporting, he received the squad number 7 shirt, which had previously been worn by such United players as George Best, Eric Cantona and David Beckham.[47] Wearing the number 7 became an extra source of motivation for Ronaldo.[48] A key element in his development during his time in England proved to be Ferguson, of whom he later said: \"He\'s been my father in sport, one of the most important and influential factors in my career.\"[49]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo playing for Manchester United against Chelsea during the 2005–06 Premier League season\r\nRonaldo made his debut as a substitute in a 4–0 home win over Bolton Wanderers in the Premier League on 16 August 2003.[50] His performance earned praise from Best, who hailed it as \"undoubtedly the most exciting debut\" he had ever seen.[43] Ronaldo scored his first goal for Manchester United with a free-kick in a 3–0 win over Portsmouth on 1 November.[51] Towards the end of the season, he received the first red card of his career.[52] Ronaldo ended his first season in English football by scoring the opening goal in United\'s 3–0 win over Millwall in the 2004 FA Cup Final, earning his first trophy.[53] BBC pundit Alan Hansen described him as the star of the final.[54] The British press had been critical of Ronaldo during the season for his \"elaborate\" step-overs in trying to beat opponents,[55] but teammate Gary Neville said he was \"not a show pony, but the real thing\", and predicted he would become a world-class player.[56]\r\n\r\n\"He has got the tricks and party pieces, we know that, but they\'re not much good unless there is something at the end of it all. We still have to remember, of course, that the lad is only 19 years of age. Considering that, you have to say he has got massive talent. His feet are mesmerising at times, and if he can couple that with some consistently good crossing, the future looks frightening.\"\r\n\r\n—Former BBC pundit Alan Hansen commenting on Ronaldo after his first season.[54]\r\nAt the start of 2005, Ronaldo played two of his best matches of the 2004–05 season, producing a goal and an assist against Aston Villa and scoring twice against rivals Arsenal.[57][58] Ronaldo won his second trophy in English football, the Football League Cup, after scoring the third goal in United\'s 4–0 final win over Wigan Athletic.[59]\r\n\r\nDuring his third season in England, Ronaldo was involved in several incidents. Ronaldo clashed with a teammate, striker Ruud van Nistelrooy, who took offence at the winger\'s showboating style of play.[60] Following the 2006 FIFA World Cup, in which he was involved in an incident where club teammate Wayne Rooney was sent off,[61] Ronaldo publicly asked for a transfer, lamenting the lack of support he felt he had received from the club over the incident.[62] United denied the possibility of him leaving the club.[63] Although his World Cup altercation with Rooney resulted in Ronaldo being booed throughout the 2006–07 season,[64] it proved to be his break-out year, as he broke the 20-goal barrier for the first time and won his first Premier League title.[65]\r\n\r\n2007–2009: Collective and individual success and Ballon d\'Or\r\n\r\nRonaldo playing for Manchester United during the 2006–07 Premier League season\r\nIn the 2006–07 season, he amassed a host of personal awards for the season, winning the Professional Footballers\' Association\'s Player\'s Player, Fans\' Player, Young Player of the Year awards, and the Football Writers\' Association\'s Footballer of the Year award,[66][67] becoming the first player to win all four main PFA and FWA honours.[68] Ronaldo was named runner-up to Kaká for the 2007 Ballon d\'Or,[69] and came third, behind Kaká and Lionel Messi, in the running for the 2007 FIFA World Player of the Year award.[70]\r\n\r\nRonaldo scored his first hat-trick for United in a 6–0 win against Newcastle United on 12 January 2008.[71] His 31 league goals earned him the Premier League Golden Boot,[72] as well as the European Golden Shoe, which made him the first winger to win the latter award.[73] He additionally received the PFA Players\' Player of the Year and FWA Footballer of the Year awards for the second consecutive season.[74][75] United reached the final against Chelsea in Moscow on 21 May, where, despite his opening goal being negated by an equaliser and his penalty kick being saved in the shoot-out,[76] United emerged victorious, winning 6–5 on penalties after a 1–1 draw at the end of 120 minutes.[77][78] As the Champions League top scorer, Ronaldo was named the UEFA Club Footballer of the Year.[79] With his 2008 Ballon d\'Or and 2008 FIFA World Player of the Year, Ronaldo became United\'s first Ballon d\'Or winner since Best in 1968,[80] and the first Premier League player to be named the FIFA World Player of the Year.[81]\r\n\r\nShortly after, Ronaldo was linked to a move to Real Madrid, United filed a tampering complaint with governing body FIFA over Madrid\'s alleged pursuit of their player, but they declined to take action.[82] and he remained at United for another year.[83] His match-winning goal in the second leg against Porto, a 40-yard strike, earned him the inaugural FIFA Puskás Award, presented by FIFA in recognition of the best goal of the year;[84] he later called it the best goal he had ever scored.[85] United advanced to the final in Rome,[86] where he made little impact in United\'s 2–0 defeat to Barcelona.[87]\r\n\r\nReal Madrid (2009–2018)\r\n2009–2015: World record transfer and consecutive Ballon d\'Or wins\r\nIn 2009, Ronaldo transferred to Real Madrid for a then world record £80 million.[88] At least 80,000 fans attended his presentation at the Santiago Bernabéu, surpassing the 25-year record of 75,000 fans who had welcomed Diego Maradona at Napoli.[89]\r\n\r\nRonaldo made his La Liga debut against Deportivo La Coruña on 29 August, scoring a penalty in a 3–2 home win.[90] He scored in each of his first four league games, the first Madrid player to do so.[91] His first Champions League goals for the club followed with two free kicks in the first group match against Zürich.[92] His strong start to the season was interrupted when he suffered an ankle injury in October while on international duty, which kept him sidelined for seven weeks.[93][94] Despite scoring 33 goals in all competitions and contributing to Real Madrid\'s 96 points in La Liga, his first season with Madrid ended trophyless.[95]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo scored 46 league goals during the La Liga championship success in his third season in Spain.\r\nFollowing Raúl\'s departure, Ronaldo was given No. 7 for the 2010–11 season and scored 53 goals, helping Madrid win the Copa del Rey, scoring the winning goal against rivals Barcelona in the El Clásico, his first trophy with Madrid.[96] He also became the first player in La Liga to score 40 goals.[97] In addition to the Pichichi Trophy, Ronaldo won the European Golden Shoe for a second time, becoming the first player to win the award in different leagues.[98]\r\n\r\nThe following season saw Ronaldo score 60 goals across all competitions,[99] leading Madrid to their first league title in four years with a record 100 points and his runner-up finish to Lionel Messi in the 2011 FIFA Ballon d\'Or.[100] He scored his 100th league goal for Madrid in a 5–1 win over Real Sociedad on 24 March 2012, breaking the previous club record held by Ferenc Puskás.[101] In the 2012–13 season, he scored his first hat-trick in the Champions League in a 4–1 win over Ajax.[102] Four days later, he became the first player to score in six successive Clásicos when he hit a brace in a 2–2 draw at Camp Nou.[103] His performances again saw Ronaldo voted second in the running for the 2012 FIFA Ballon d\'Or, behind four-time winner Messi.[104]\r\n\r\nFollowing the 2012–13 winter break, Ronaldo captained Madrid for the first time in an official match, scoring twice to lift 10-man Madrid to a 4–3 win over Sociedad on 6 January.[105] He subsequently became the first non-Spanish player in 60 years to captain Madrid in El Clasico on 30 January, a match which also marked his 500th club appearance.[106]\r\n\r\nIn 2013–14 season, Ronaldo was joined at the club by winger Gareth Bale and together with striker Karim Benzema, they formed an attacking trio popularly dubbed \"BBC\", an acronym of Bale, Benzema and Cristiano, and a play on the name of the British public service broadcaster, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC).[107] He continued prolific scoring, with 69 goals in 2013, winning the 2013 FIFA Ballon d\'Or,[108] and the FIFA World Player of the Year award, for the first time in his career.[109]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo scored a record 17 UEFA Champions League goals during the 2013–14 season en route to La Décima.\r\nConcurrently with his individual achievements, Ronaldo enjoyed his greatest team success in Spain to date, as he helped Madrid win La Décima, their tenth European Cup, scoring a penalty in the 120th minute of the 4–1 final win over city rivals Atlético Madrid, becoming the first player to score in two European Cup finals for two different winning teams.[110] As the competition\'s top goalscorer for the third time, with a record 17 goals,[111] he was named the UEFA Best Player in Europe.[112] Ronaldo scored 31 goals in 30 league games, which earned him the Pichichi and the European Golden Shoe, along with Liverpool\'s Luis Suárez[113] On 4 May, Ronaldo scored a back-heeled volley in the closing moments of the match against Valencia, voted goal of the season by the Liga Nacional de Fútbol Profesional (LFP),[114] giving him the Best Player in La Liga award.[115]\r\n\r\nDuring the 2014–15 season, Ronaldo set a new personal best of 61 goals, and after winning the 2014 FIFA Club World Cup,[116] Ronaldo received the 2014 Ballon d\'Or,[117] joining Johan Cruyff, Michel Platini and Marco van Basten as a three-time recipient.[118] Madrid finished in second place in La Liga and exited at the semi-final stage in the Champions League.[119] With 10 goals, he finished as top scorer for a third consecutive season, alongside Messi and Neymar.[120] On 5 April, he scored five goals in a game for the first time in his career, including an eight-minute hat-trick, in a 9–1 rout of Granada.[121] His 300th goal for his club followed three days later in a 2–0 win against Rayo Vallecano.[122] He finished the season with 48 goals, winning a second consecutive Pichichi and the European Golden Shoe for a record fourth time.[123]\r\n\r\n2015–2018: All-time Madrid top scorer and Fifth Ballon d\'Or\r\nCristiano Ronaldo became Real Madrid\'s all-time top scorer on 12 September 2015 against Espanyol, netting 230 goals in 203 matches, surpassing the previous record holder, Raúl.[124] Ronaldo also became the all-time top scorer in the Champions League with a hat-trick in the first group match against Shakhtar Donetsk, having finished the previous season level with Messi on 77 goals.[125] Two goals against Malmö FF in a 2–0 away win on 30 September saw him reach the milestone of 500 career goals for club and country.[126] He won the 2016 Ballon d\'Or, his fourth, and the inaugural 2016 The Best FIFA Men\'s Player, a revival of the former FIFA World Player of the Year, largely owing to his success with Portugal in winning Euro 2016.[127]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo in the 2018 UEFA Champions League Final, his final game for Real Madrid\r\nIn the 2016–17 UEFA Champions League quarter-finals against Bayern in April, Ronaldo scored both goals in a 2–1 away win which saw him make history by becoming the first player to reach 100 goals in UEFA club competition.[128] On 17 May, Ronaldo overtook Jimmy Greaves as the all-time top scorer in the top five European leagues, scoring twice against Celta de Vigo.[129] He finished the season with 42 goals in all competitions as he helped Madrid to win their first La Liga title since 2012.[130] In the Champions League Final, Ronaldo scored two goals in a 4–1 victory over Juventus to take him to 12 goals for the season, making him the competition\'s top goalscorer for the fifth straight season (sixth overall), as well as the first player to score in three finals in the Champions League era; the second goal was the 600th of his senior career.[131] Madrid also became the first team to win back-to-back finals in the Champions League era.[132]\r\n\r\nOn 23 October, his performances throughout 2017 saw him awarded The Best FIFA Men\'s Player award for the second consecutive year.[133] A day later, Ronaldo won the 2017 Ballon d\'Or, receiving his fifth-time award on the Eiffel Tower in Paris.[134] On 3 April 2024, Ronaldo scored the first two goals in a 3–0 away win against Juventus in the quarter-finals of the 2017–18 UEFA Champions League, with his second goal being an acrobatic bicycle kick. Described as a \"PlayStation goal\" by Juventus defender Andrea Barzagli, with Ronaldo\'s foot approximately 7 ft 7 in (2.31 m) off the ground, it garnered him a standing ovation from the opposing fans in the stadium as well as a plethora of plaudits from peers, pundits and coaches.[135] In the final on 26 May, Madrid defeated Liverpool 3–1, winning Ronaldo his fifth Champions League title, the first player to do so.[136] He finished as the top scorer of the tournament for the sixth consecutive season with 15 goals.[137] After the final, Ronaldo referred to his time with Madrid in the past tense, sparking speculation that he could leave the club.[138]\r\n\r\nJuventus (2018–2021)\r\nRonaldo joined Juventus in 2018 for €100 million, the transfer was the highest ever for a player over 30 years old and the highest paid by an Italian club.[139] Upon signing, Ronaldo cited his need for a new challenge as his rationale for departing Madrid,[140] but later attributed the transfer to the lack of support he felt was shown by club president Florentino Pérez.[141]\r\n\r\n2018–2020: Consecutive Serie A titles\r\nOn 18 August, Ronaldo made his debut in a 3–2 away win against Chievo Verona.[142] On 19 September, in his first Champions League match for Juve, he was sent off against Valencia, his first red card in 154 Champions League appearances.[143] In the reverse (home) leg against Valencia, Cristiano won 100 Champions League matches, becoming the first ever player to do so.[144]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo playing for Juventus against Torino in November 2019\r\nRonaldo won his first trophy with the club on 16 January 2019, the 2018 Supercoppa Italiana, after he scored the only goal from a header against AC Milan.[145] On 10 February, Ronaldo scored in a 3–0 win over Sassuolo, the ninth consecutive away game in which he had scored in the league, equalling Giuseppe Signori\'s single season Serie A record of most consecutive away games with at least one goal.[146] On 12 March, Ronaldo scored a hat-trick in a 3–0 home win against Atlético in the second leg of the Champions League round of 16, helping Juventus overcome a two-goal deficit to reach the quarter-finals.[147] On 20 April, Ronaldo played in the scudetto clinching game against Fiorentina, as Juventus won their eighth successive title after a 2–1 home win, thereby becoming the first player to win league titles in England, Spain and Italy.[148] With 21 goals and eight assists, Ronaldo won the league award for Most Valuable Player.[149]\r\n\r\nOn 1 October, he reached several milestones in Juventus\'s 3–0 Champions League group stage win over Bayer Leverkusen including breaking Iker Casillas\' record for most Champions League wins of all time.[150] On 18 December, Ronaldo leapt to a height of 8 ft 5 in (2.57 m), higher than the crossbar, to head the winning goal in a 2–1 away win against Sampdoria.[151] He scored his first Serie A hat-trick on 6 January 2020, in a 4–0 home win against Cagliari and became only the second player to score hat-tricks in the Premier League, La Liga and Serie A.[152] On 22 February, Ronaldo scored for a record-equalling 11th consecutive league game, alongside Gabriel Batistuta and Fabio Quagliarella, in what was his 1,000th senior professional game, a 2–1 away win against SPAL.[153] On 22 June, he scored a penalty in a 2–0 away win over Bologna, overtaking Rui Costa to become the highest scoring Portuguese player in Serie A history.[154] On 20 July, Ronaldo scored twice in a 2–1 home win over Lazio; his first goal was his 50th in Serie A. He became the first player in history to reach 50 goals in the Premier League, La Liga and Serie A, and becoming the second player after Edin Džeko to score 50 goals in three of Europe\'s top five major leagues.[155] Moreover, he became the oldest player, at the age of 35 years and 166 days, to score over 30 goals in one of the five top European leagues since Ronnie Rooke with Arsenal in 1948.[156] On 26 July, Ronaldo scored the opening goal in a 2–0 home win over Sampdoria as Juventus were crowned Serie A champions for a ninth consecutive time.[157] On 7 August, Ronaldo scored a brace in a 2–1 home win against Lyon in the second leg of the Champions League round of 16, which saw him finish the season with 37 goals in all competitions; the tally allowed him to break Borel\'s club record of 36 goals in a single season.[158]\r\n\r\n2020–2021: 100 Juve goals, Capocannoniere, and departure\r\nRonaldo played his 100th match in all competitions for Juventus on 13 December, scoring two penalties in a 3–1 away win over Genoa in the league to bring his goal tally to 79.[159] On 2 March 2021, he scored a goal in a 3–0 win over Spezia in his 600th league match, to become the first player to score at least 20 goals in 12 consecutive seasons in the top five leagues of Europe.[160] On 12 May, Ronaldo scored a goal in a 3–1 away win over Sassuolo to reach his 100th goal for Juventus in all competitions on his 131st appearance, becoming the fastest Juventus player to achieve the feat.[161] With Juventus\'s victory in the 2021 Coppa Italia Final on 19 May, Ronaldo became the first player in history to win every major domestic trophy in England, Spain and Italy.[162] Ronaldo ended the season with 29 league goals, winning the Capocannoniere award for highest goalscorer and becoming the first footballer to finish as top scorer in the English, Spanish and Italian leagues.[163]\r\n\r\nThe start of the following season came amid reports Ronaldo would depart the club before the closure of the transfer window,[164] despite Ronaldo and his agent Jorge Mendes reaching a verbal agreement with Manchester City over personal terms,[165] but the club pulled out of the deal,[166] and later it was confirmed that City\'s rivals Manchester United, Ronaldo\'s former club, were in advanced talks to sign him,[167][168] while former manager Alex Ferguson and several ex-teammates had been in contact to persuade him to re-sign for United.[169][170]', '<p>The provided text is an extensive overview of the life and career of Cristiano Ronaldo, one of the most notable footballers in history. The narrative unfolds chronologically, detailing his achievements, personal struggles, professional milestones, and the significant impact he has had on football and beyond. An exhaustive analysis of this text will encompass its major ideas, structure, tone, language use, and underlying themes.</p>\n<h3>Major Ideas</h3>\n<p>The overarching theme of the text is the remarkable career of Cristiano Ronaldo, from his humble beginnings in Madeira to becoming a global sports icon. The text contains several major ideas that reflect different aspects of his life:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Professional Accomplishments</strong>: The text highlights Ronaldo\'s extensive list of accolades, including multiple Ballon d\'Or awards, Champions League titles, and international success with the Portuguese national team. Specific statistics like record appearances, goals, and assists underline his exceptional talent.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Rising from Adversity</strong>: Ronaldo\'s early life, marked by poverty and familial challenges, sets a backdrop for his later success. The mention of his mother considering abortion due to financial struggles adds depth to his story, illustrating the odds he overcame. </p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Influence and Marketability</strong>: The narrative explores Ronaldo\'s status as a marketable athlete and a global brand, addressing his financial success and massive following on social media, which contributes to his image as a prominent figure in contemporary sports culture.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Personal Struggles and Health</strong>: The text does not shy away from Ronaldo\'s personal struggles, including issues during his childhood and heart surgery at a young age. These elements humanize him and present a more rounded view of the athlete.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Competitive Nature and Rivalries</strong>: Ronaldo’s rivalry with fellow player Lionel Messi is a recurring theme, underscoring the competitive spirit that defines both players\' careers and pushing them to excel.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Structure and Flow</h3>\n<p>The organization of the document is both coherent and logical. It begins with a succinct introduction that encapsulates Ronaldo’s significance in football. The text transitions smoothly into his early life, providing context before delving into his club career in various stages, ultimately covering his time with multiple clubs (Sporting CP, Manchester United, Real Madrid, Juventus, and Al Nassr). Each section builds upon the last, showcasing the progression of Ronaldo\'s career and personal growth, which maintains the reader\'s engagement.</p>\n<h3>Tone and Style</h3>\n<p>The tone of the text is predominantly factual and celebratory, conveying a reverence for Ronaldo\'s accomplishments. The language is straightforward, reinforcing the authoritative nature of the text. Descriptive phrases like &quot;widely regarded as one of the greatest players of all time&quot; reflect an admiring perspective, while the presentation of statistical achievements speaks to his professional excellence.</p>\n<p>There is a subtle reliance on celebratory adjectives and superlatives, emphasizing the extraordinary nature of his career. For instance, phrases like &quot;one of the greatest players of all time&quot; and &quot;top goalscorer of all time&quot; elevate Ronaldo in a way that fosters admiration from the audience. The tone could also be interpreted as slightly hagiographic, portraying him as an almost mythical figure in sports.</p>\n<h3>Language Use and Diction</h3>\n<p>The author employs a mix of formal and sporting lexicon, using terms familiar to football audiences while maintaining accessibility for general readers. Words and phrases such as &quot;European Golden Shoes,&quot; &quot;integral to the team,&quot; and &quot;record transfer fee&quot; are specific to the realm of football, grounding the text in the sport\'s culture. The statistical information helps contextualize Ronaldo\'s achievements, making them tangible for readers.</p>\n<p>The use of descriptive imagery—such as “acrobatic bicycle kick,” “head the winning goal,” and “elaborate step-overs”—further enriches the text, allowing readers to visualize critical moments in Ronaldo’s career.</p>\n<h3>Sentence Patterns and Grammatical Techniques</h3>\n<p>The text predominantly employs a declarative style, giving straightforward accounts of events. This choice allows for clarity and directness, critical in biographical writing where detail is essential. The sentences are often comprehensive, filled with facts and figures that construct a robust account of Ronaldo’s career trajectory and achievements.</p>\n<p>The author also utilizes direct quotes from notable figures, such as George Best and pundits, adding credibility and reinforcing the impact Ronaldo has had on the football community. This technique introduces a multi-dimensional view of him, as it combines perspectives from peers and experts alongside factual narrative.</p>\n<h3>Themes and Nuances</h3>\n<p>Several subtle themes emerge throughout the text:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Resilience and Triumph</strong>: Ronaldo\'s journey from a modest upbringing to global superstardom highlights themes of resilience and determination. The narrative illustrates how he transformed his hardships into a driving force for success, embodying the notion that talent coupled with hard work leads to greatness.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Cultural Impact</strong>: The text underlines Ronaldo\'s influence not just in sports but as a worldwide cultural figure. His marketability and social media presence signify a transition of athletes into brand icons in the modern world.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Legacy and Rivalry</strong>: The contrast with Lionel Messi provides a nuanced examination of athletic rivalry and legacy. Ronaldo\'s career metrics stand alongside Messi\'s, creating a narrative rich with comparisons and responses that showcase the nature of competition at the highest level.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Passion for the Game</strong>: References to Ronaldo’s childhood dreams and his idolization of other footballers paint a portrait of someone who has been deeply passionate about the sport since childhood. This theme reinforces the idea that personal ambition, when combined with drive, can indeed lead to remarkable achievements.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In conclusion, the text serves as a comprehensive and detailed account of Cristiano Ronaldo\'s life and career, celebrating his success while also reflecting on the adversities he faced. The careful structuring, engaging tone, and rich language all contribute to a narrative that is both informative and inspiring, capturing the essence of a figure who has profoundly shaped modern football. The underlying themes add depth to his story, making it not only a chronicle of success but also a testament to human perseverance.</p>', 'text analysis', '', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750feb11fe9c4.45598098', '2024-12-04 18:15:29', '2024-12-04 18:15:29');
INSERT INTO `text_analysis` (`id`, `user_id`, `text_content`, `analysis_result`, `type_of_analysis`, `evaluation`, `status`, `analysis_evaluation_code`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(103, 9, 'Cristiano Ronaldo dos Santos Aveiro GOIH ComM (Portuguese pronunciation: [kɾiʃˈtjɐnu ʁɔˈnaldu] ⓘ; born 5 February 1985) is a Portuguese professional footballer who plays as a forward for and captains both the Saudi Pro League club Al Nassr and the Portugal national team. Widely regarded as one of the greatest players of all time, Ronaldo has won numerous individual accolades throughout his career, such as five Ballon d\'Or awards, a record three UEFA Men\'s Player of the Year Awards, four European Golden Shoes, and was named five times the world\'s best player by FIFA,[note 3] the most by a European player. He has won 33 trophies in his career, including seven league titles, five UEFA Champions Leagues, the UEFA European Championship and the UEFA Nations League. Ronaldo holds the records for most appearances (183), goals (140) and assists (42) in the Champions League, most appearances (30), assists (8), goals in the European Championship (14), international appearances (217) and international goals (135). He is one of the few players to have made over 1,200 professional career appearances, the most by an outfield player, and has scored over 900 official senior career goals for club and country, making him the top goalscorer of all time.[note 4]\r\n\r\nRonaldo began his senior career with Sporting CP, before signing with Manchester United in 2003, winning the FA Cup in his first season. He went on to win three consecutive Premier League titles, the Champions League and the FIFA Club World Cup; at age 23, he won his first Ballon d\'Or. Ronaldo was the subject of the then-most expensive association football transfer when he signed for Real Madrid in 2009 in a transfer worth €94 million (£80 million). He became a key contributor and formed an attacking trio with Karim Benzema and Gareth Bale which was integral to the team winning four Champions Leagues from 2014 to 2018, including La Décima. During this period, he won back-to-back Ballons d\'Or in 2013 and 2014, and again in 2016 and 2017, and was runner-up three times behind Lionel Messi, his perceived career rival. He also became the club\'s all-time top goalscorer and the all-time top scorer in the Champions League, and finished as the competition\'s top scorer for six consecutive seasons between 2012 and 2018. With Real, Ronaldo won four Champions Leagues, two La Liga titles, two Copas del Rey, two UEFA Super Cups and three Club World Cups. In 2018, he signed for Juventus in a transfer worth an initial €100 million (£88 million), the most expensive transfer for an Italian club and for a player over 30 years old. He won two Serie A titles, two Supercoppa Italiana trophies and a Coppa Italia, became the inaugural Serie A Most Valuable Player, and the first footballer to finish as top scorer in the English, Spanish and Italian leagues. He returned to Manchester United in 2021, finishing his only full season as the club\'s top scorer, before his contract was terminated in 2022. In 2023, he signed for Al Nassr.\r\n\r\nRonaldo made his international debut for Portugal in 2003 at the age of 18 and has earned more than 200 caps, making him history\'s most-capped male player.[8] With 130 international goals, he is also the all-time top male goalscorer. Ronaldo has played in eleven major tournaments and scored in ten; he scored his first international goal at Euro 2004, where he helped Portugal reach the final. He assumed captaincy of the national team in July 2008. In 2015, Ronaldo was named the best Portuguese player of all time by the Portuguese Football Federation. The following year, he led Portugal to their first major tournament title at Euro 2016, and received the Silver Boot as the second-highest goalscorer of the tournament. This achievement saw him receive his fourth Ballon d\'Or. He also led them to victory in the inaugural UEFA Nations League in 2019, receiving the top scorer award in the finals, and later received the Golden Boot as top scorer of Euro 2020. The same tournament, he broke the record of most international goals scored in men\'s football and became the player with the most international caps in men\'s football in 2023.\r\n\r\nOne of the world\'s most marketable and famous athletes, Ronaldo was ranked the world\'s highest-paid athlete by Forbes in 2016, 2017, 2023, and 2024 and the world\'s most famous athlete by ESPN from 2016 to 2019. Time included him on their list of the 100 most influential people in the world in 2014. Ronaldo is the most popular sportsperson on social media: he counts over 1 billion total followers across Facebook, Twitter, YouTube and Instagram, making him the first person to achieve that feat. In 2020, Ronaldo was named to the Ballon d\'Or Dream Team and he is the first footballer and the third sportsman to earn US$1 billion in his career.\r\n\r\nEarly life\r\nCristiano Ronaldo dos Santos Aveiro was born on 5 February 1985 in the São Pedro parish of Funchal, the capital of the Portuguese island of Madeira, and grew up in the nearby parish of Santo António.[9][10] He is the fourth and youngest child of Maria Dolores dos Santos Viveiros Aveiro, who worked as a cook in the hospitality industry and a cleaning woman,[11][12] and José Dinis Aveiro, a municipal gardener at the Junta de Freguesia of Santo António and part-time kit man for football club Andorinha.[13][14][15] His great-grandmother on his father\'s side, Isabel da Piedade, an African woman, was born in the island of São Vicente, in what was then Portuguese Cape Verde, and moved to Madeira Island at 16.[16][17] He has one older brother, Hugo, and two older sisters, Elma and Liliana Cátia \"Kátia\".[2] He was named after actor and U.S. President Ronald Reagan, whom his father was a fan of.[18] His mother revealed that she wanted to abort him due to poverty, his father\'s alcoholism, and having too many children already, but her doctor refused to perform the procedure.[19][20] Ronaldo grew up in an impoverished Catholic home, sharing a room with all his siblings.[21]\r\n\r\nAs a child, Ronaldo played for Andorinha from 1992 to 1995,[22] where his father was the kit man,[13] and later spent two years with Nacional. In 1997, aged 12, he went on a three-day trial with Sporting CP, who signed him for a fee of £1,500.[23] He subsequently moved from Madeira to Lisbon to join Sporting CP\'s youth system.[23] By age 14, while struggling with his school duties and responsibilities in Escola EB2 de Telheiras, his school in the Telheiras area of Lisbon, Ronaldo believed he had the ability to play semi-professionally and agreed with his mother and his tutor at Sporting CP, Leonel Pontes,[24] to cease his education to focus entirely on football.[25][26] With a troubled life as a student,[27] and although living in Lisbon area away from his Madeiran family,[28][29] he did not complete schooling beyond the 6th grade.[30][31] While popular with other students at school, he had been expelled after throwing a chair at his teacher, who he said had \"disrespected\" him.[25] One year later, he was diagnosed with tachycardia, a condition that could have forced him to give up playing football.[32] Ronaldo underwent heart surgery where a laser was used to cauterise multiple cardiac pathways into one, altering his resting heart rate.[33] He was discharged from the hospital hours after the procedure and resumed training a few days later.[34] In 2021, Cristiano Ronaldo\'s mother, Dolores Aveiro, stated in an interview for Sporting CP\'s official television channel (Sporting TV) that her son would be a bricklayer if he hadn\'t become a professional football player.[35]\r\n\r\nGrowing up, Ronaldo idolised the Brazilian footballers Ronaldinho and Ronaldo Nazário, and has described them as leaving \"a beautiful history in football\".[36]\r\n\r\nClub career\r\nMain article: Career of Cristiano Ronaldo § Club career\r\nSporting CP (2002–2003)\r\nAfter impressing in Sporting\'s youth teams, he was promoted to the main team by first-team manager László Bölöni. At age 17, on 14 August 2002, he played his first official match for the first team, in a UEFA Champions League qualifying round at José Alvalade Stadium against Inter Milan,[37] and his Primeira Liga debut, took place a month later against Braga, and on 7 October, he scored two goals against Moreirense in their 3–0 win.[38] Over the course of the 2002–03 season, his representatives suggested the player to Liverpool manager Gérard Houllier and Barcelona president Joan Laporta.[39] Manager Arsène Wenger, who was interested in signing Ronaldo, met with him at Arsenal\'s stadium in November to discuss a possible transfer.[40]\r\n\r\nManchester United manager Alex Ferguson was determined to acquire Ronaldo on a permanent move urgently, after Sporting defeated United 3–1 at the inauguration of the Estádio José Alvalade on 6 August 2003. Initially, United had planned to sign Ronaldo and loan him back to Sporting for a year.[41] Having been impressed by him, the United players urged Ferguson to sign him. After the game, Ferguson agreed to pay Sporting £12.24 million[41] for what he considered to be \"one of the most exciting young players\" he had ever seen.[42]\r\n\r\nManchester United (2003–2009)\r\n2003–2007: Development and breakthrough\r\n\"There have been a few players described as \'the new George Best\' over the years, but this is the first time it\'s been a compliment to me.\"\r\n\r\n—Former Manchester United player George Best hails the 18-year-old Cristiano Ronaldo in 2003.[43]\r\nManchester United\'s signed Ronaldo for £12 million on 12 August 2003,[44] an England record for a teenager.[45] This also made him the first Portuguese player to sign for the club.[46]\r\n\r\nAlthough he requested the number 28, his number at Sporting, he received the squad number 7 shirt, which had previously been worn by such United players as George Best, Eric Cantona and David Beckham.[47] Wearing the number 7 became an extra source of motivation for Ronaldo.[48] A key element in his development during his time in England proved to be Ferguson, of whom he later said: \"He\'s been my father in sport, one of the most important and influential factors in my career.\"[49]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo playing for Manchester United against Chelsea during the 2005–06 Premier League season\r\nRonaldo made his debut as a substitute in a 4–0 home win over Bolton Wanderers in the Premier League on 16 August 2003.[50] His performance earned praise from Best, who hailed it as \"undoubtedly the most exciting debut\" he had ever seen.[43] Ronaldo scored his first goal for Manchester United with a free-kick in a 3–0 win over Portsmouth on 1 November.[51] Towards the end of the season, he received the first red card of his career.[52] Ronaldo ended his first season in English football by scoring the opening goal in United\'s 3–0 win over Millwall in the 2004 FA Cup Final, earning his first trophy.[53] BBC pundit Alan Hansen described him as the star of the final.[54] The British press had been critical of Ronaldo during the season for his \"elaborate\" step-overs in trying to beat opponents,[55] but teammate Gary Neville said he was \"not a show pony, but the real thing\", and predicted he would become a world-class player.[56]\r\n\r\n\"He has got the tricks and party pieces, we know that, but they\'re not much good unless there is something at the end of it all. We still have to remember, of course, that the lad is only 19 years of age. Considering that, you have to say he has got massive talent. His feet are mesmerising at times, and if he can couple that with some consistently good crossing, the future looks frightening.\"\r\n\r\n—Former BBC pundit Alan Hansen commenting on Ronaldo after his first season.[54]\r\nAt the start of 2005, Ronaldo played two of his best matches of the 2004–05 season, producing a goal and an assist against Aston Villa and scoring twice against rivals Arsenal.[57][58] Ronaldo won his second trophy in English football, the Football League Cup, after scoring the third goal in United\'s 4–0 final win over Wigan Athletic.[59]\r\n\r\nDuring his third season in England, Ronaldo was involved in several incidents. Ronaldo clashed with a teammate, striker Ruud van Nistelrooy, who took offence at the winger\'s showboating style of play.[60] Following the 2006 FIFA World Cup, in which he was involved in an incident where club teammate Wayne Rooney was sent off,[61] Ronaldo publicly asked for a transfer, lamenting the lack of support he felt he had received from the club over the incident.[62] United denied the possibility of him leaving the club.[63] Although his World Cup altercation with Rooney resulted in Ronaldo being booed throughout the 2006–07 season,[64] it proved to be his break-out year, as he broke the 20-goal barrier for the first time and won his first Premier League title.[65]\r\n\r\n2007–2009: Collective and individual success and Ballon d\'Or\r\n\r\nRonaldo playing for Manchester United during the 2006–07 Premier League season\r\nIn the 2006–07 season, he amassed a host of personal awards for the season, winning the Professional Footballers\' Association\'s Player\'s Player, Fans\' Player, Young Player of the Year awards, and the Football Writers\' Association\'s Footballer of the Year award,[66][67] becoming the first player to win all four main PFA and FWA honours.[68] Ronaldo was named runner-up to Kaká for the 2007 Ballon d\'Or,[69] and came third, behind Kaká and Lionel Messi, in the running for the 2007 FIFA World Player of the Year award.[70]\r\n\r\nRonaldo scored his first hat-trick for United in a 6–0 win against Newcastle United on 12 January 2008.[71] His 31 league goals earned him the Premier League Golden Boot,[72] as well as the European Golden Shoe, which made him the first winger to win the latter award.[73] He additionally received the PFA Players\' Player of the Year and FWA Footballer of the Year awards for the second consecutive season.[74][75] United reached the final against Chelsea in Moscow on 21 May, where, despite his opening goal being negated by an equaliser and his penalty kick being saved in the shoot-out,[76] United emerged victorious, winning 6–5 on penalties after a 1–1 draw at the end of 120 minutes.[77][78] As the Champions League top scorer, Ronaldo was named the UEFA Club Footballer of the Year.[79] With his 2008 Ballon d\'Or and 2008 FIFA World Player of the Year, Ronaldo became United\'s first Ballon d\'Or winner since Best in 1968,[80] and the first Premier League player to be named the FIFA World Player of the Year.[81]\r\n\r\nShortly after, Ronaldo was linked to a move to Real Madrid, United filed a tampering complaint with governing body FIFA over Madrid\'s alleged pursuit of their player, but they declined to take action.[82] and he remained at United for another year.[83] His match-winning goal in the second leg against Porto, a 40-yard strike, earned him the inaugural FIFA Puskás Award, presented by FIFA in recognition of the best goal of the year;[84] he later called it the best goal he had ever scored.[85] United advanced to the final in Rome,[86] where he made little impact in United\'s 2–0 defeat to Barcelona.[87]\r\n\r\nReal Madrid (2009–2018)\r\n2009–2015: World record transfer and consecutive Ballon d\'Or wins\r\nIn 2009, Ronaldo transferred to Real Madrid for a then world record £80 million.[88] At least 80,000 fans attended his presentation at the Santiago Bernabéu, surpassing the 25-year record of 75,000 fans who had welcomed Diego Maradona at Napoli.[89]\r\n\r\nRonaldo made his La Liga debut against Deportivo La Coruña on 29 August, scoring a penalty in a 3–2 home win.[90] He scored in each of his first four league games, the first Madrid player to do so.[91] His first Champions League goals for the club followed with two free kicks in the first group match against Zürich.[92] His strong start to the season was interrupted when he suffered an ankle injury in October while on international duty, which kept him sidelined for seven weeks.[93][94] Despite scoring 33 goals in all competitions and contributing to Real Madrid\'s 96 points in La Liga, his first season with Madrid ended trophyless.[95]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo scored 46 league goals during the La Liga championship success in his third season in Spain.\r\nFollowing Raúl\'s departure, Ronaldo was given No. 7 for the 2010–11 season and scored 53 goals, helping Madrid win the Copa del Rey, scoring the winning goal against rivals Barcelona in the El Clásico, his first trophy with Madrid.[96] He also became the first player in La Liga to score 40 goals.[97] In addition to the Pichichi Trophy, Ronaldo won the European Golden Shoe for a second time, becoming the first player to win the award in different leagues.[98]\r\n\r\nThe following season saw Ronaldo score 60 goals across all competitions,[99] leading Madrid to their first league title in four years with a record 100 points and his runner-up finish to Lionel Messi in the 2011 FIFA Ballon d\'Or.[100] He scored his 100th league goal for Madrid in a 5–1 win over Real Sociedad on 24 March 2012, breaking the previous club record held by Ferenc Puskás.[101] In the 2012–13 season, he scored his first hat-trick in the Champions League in a 4–1 win over Ajax.[102] Four days later, he became the first player to score in six successive Clásicos when he hit a brace in a 2–2 draw at Camp Nou.[103] His performances again saw Ronaldo voted second in the running for the 2012 FIFA Ballon d\'Or, behind four-time winner Messi.[104]\r\n\r\nFollowing the 2012–13 winter break, Ronaldo captained Madrid for the first time in an official match, scoring twice to lift 10-man Madrid to a 4–3 win over Sociedad on 6 January.[105] He subsequently became the first non-Spanish player in 60 years to captain Madrid in El Clasico on 30 January, a match which also marked his 500th club appearance.[106]\r\n\r\nIn 2013–14 season, Ronaldo was joined at the club by winger Gareth Bale and together with striker Karim Benzema, they formed an attacking trio popularly dubbed \"BBC\", an acronym of Bale, Benzema and Cristiano, and a play on the name of the British public service broadcaster, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC).[107] He continued prolific scoring, with 69 goals in 2013, winning the 2013 FIFA Ballon d\'Or,[108] and the FIFA World Player of the Year award, for the first time in his career.[109]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo scored a record 17 UEFA Champions League goals during the 2013–14 season en route to La Décima.\r\nConcurrently with his individual achievements, Ronaldo enjoyed his greatest team success in Spain to date, as he helped Madrid win La Décima, their tenth European Cup, scoring a penalty in the 120th minute of the 4–1 final win over city rivals Atlético Madrid, becoming the first player to score in two European Cup finals for two different winning teams.[110] As the competition\'s top goalscorer for the third time, with a record 17 goals,[111] he was named the UEFA Best Player in Europe.[112] Ronaldo scored 31 goals in 30 league games, which earned him the Pichichi and the European Golden Shoe, along with Liverpool\'s Luis Suárez[113] On 4 May, Ronaldo scored a back-heeled volley in the closing moments of the match against Valencia, voted goal of the season by the Liga Nacional de Fútbol Profesional (LFP),[114] giving him the Best Player in La Liga award.[115]\r\n\r\nDuring the 2014–15 season, Ronaldo set a new personal best of 61 goals, and after winning the 2014 FIFA Club World Cup,[116] Ronaldo received the 2014 Ballon d\'Or,[117] joining Johan Cruyff, Michel Platini and Marco van Basten as a three-time recipient.[118] Madrid finished in second place in La Liga and exited at the semi-final stage in the Champions League.[119] With 10 goals, he finished as top scorer for a third consecutive season, alongside Messi and Neymar.[120] On 5 April, he scored five goals in a game for the first time in his career, including an eight-minute hat-trick, in a 9–1 rout of Granada.[121] His 300th goal for his club followed three days later in a 2–0 win against Rayo Vallecano.[122] He finished the season with 48 goals, winning a second consecutive Pichichi and the European Golden Shoe for a record fourth time.[123]\r\n\r\n2015–2018: All-time Madrid top scorer and Fifth Ballon d\'Or\r\nCristiano Ronaldo became Real Madrid\'s all-time top scorer on 12 September 2015 against Espanyol, netting 230 goals in 203 matches, surpassing the previous record holder, Raúl.[124] Ronaldo also became the all-time top scorer in the Champions League with a hat-trick in the first group match against Shakhtar Donetsk, having finished the previous season level with Messi on 77 goals.[125] Two goals against Malmö FF in a 2–0 away win on 30 September saw him reach the milestone of 500 career goals for club and country.[126] He won the 2016 Ballon d\'Or, his fourth, and the inaugural 2016 The Best FIFA Men\'s Player, a revival of the former FIFA World Player of the Year, largely owing to his success with Portugal in winning Euro 2016.[127]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo in the 2018 UEFA Champions League Final, his final game for Real Madrid\r\nIn the 2016–17 UEFA Champions League quarter-finals against Bayern in April, Ronaldo scored both goals in a 2–1 away win which saw him make history by becoming the first player to reach 100 goals in UEFA club competition.[128] On 17 May, Ronaldo overtook Jimmy Greaves as the all-time top scorer in the top five European leagues, scoring twice against Celta de Vigo.[129] He finished the season with 42 goals in all competitions as he helped Madrid to win their first La Liga title since 2012.[130] In the Champions League Final, Ronaldo scored two goals in a 4–1 victory over Juventus to take him to 12 goals for the season, making him the competition\'s top goalscorer for the fifth straight season (sixth overall), as well as the first player to score in three finals in the Champions League era; the second goal was the 600th of his senior career.[131] Madrid also became the first team to win back-to-back finals in the Champions League era.[132]\r\n\r\nOn 23 October, his performances throughout 2017 saw him awarded The Best FIFA Men\'s Player award for the second consecutive year.[133] A day later, Ronaldo won the 2017 Ballon d\'Or, receiving his fifth-time award on the Eiffel Tower in Paris.[134] On 3 April 2024, Ronaldo scored the first two goals in a 3–0 away win against Juventus in the quarter-finals of the 2017–18 UEFA Champions League, with his second goal being an acrobatic bicycle kick. Described as a \"PlayStation goal\" by Juventus defender Andrea Barzagli, with Ronaldo\'s foot approximately 7 ft 7 in (2.31 m) off the ground, it garnered him a standing ovation from the opposing fans in the stadium as well as a plethora of plaudits from peers, pundits and coaches.[135] In the final on 26 May, Madrid defeated Liverpool 3–1, winning Ronaldo his fifth Champions League title, the first player to do so.[136] He finished as the top scorer of the tournament for the sixth consecutive season with 15 goals.[137] After the final, Ronaldo referred to his time with Madrid in the past tense, sparking speculation that he could leave the club.[138]\r\n\r\nJuventus (2018–2021)\r\nRonaldo joined Juventus in 2018 for €100 million, the transfer was the highest ever for a player over 30 years old and the highest paid by an Italian club.[139] Upon signing, Ronaldo cited his need for a new challenge as his rationale for departing Madrid,[140] but later attributed the transfer to the lack of support he felt was shown by club president Florentino Pérez.[141]\r\n\r\n2018–2020: Consecutive Serie A titles\r\nOn 18 August, Ronaldo made his debut in a 3–2 away win against Chievo Verona.[142] On 19 September, in his first Champions League match for Juve, he was sent off against Valencia, his first red card in 154 Champions League appearances.[143] In the reverse (home) leg against Valencia, Cristiano won 100 Champions League matches, becoming the first ever player to do so.[144]\r\n\r\n\r\nRonaldo playing for Juventus against Torino in November 2019\r\nRonaldo won his first trophy with the club on 16 January 2019, the 2018 Supercoppa Italiana, after he scored the only goal from a header against AC Milan.[145] On 10 February, Ronaldo scored in a 3–0 win over Sassuolo, the ninth consecutive away game in which he had scored in the league, equalling Giuseppe Signori\'s single season Serie A record of most consecutive away games with at least one goal.[146] On 12 March, Ronaldo scored a hat-trick in a 3–0 home win against Atlético in the second leg of the Champions League round of 16, helping Juventus overcome a two-goal deficit to reach the quarter-finals.[147] On 20 April, Ronaldo played in the scudetto clinching game against Fiorentina, as Juventus won their eighth successive title after a 2–1 home win, thereby becoming the first player to win league titles in England, Spain and Italy.[148] With 21 goals and eight assists, Ronaldo won the league award for Most Valuable Player.[149]\r\n\r\nOn 1 October, he reached several milestones in Juventus\'s 3–0 Champions League group stage win over Bayer Leverkusen including breaking Iker Casillas\' record for most Champions League wins of all time.[150] On 18 December, Ronaldo leapt to a height of 8 ft 5 in (2.57 m), higher than the crossbar, to head the winning goal in a 2–1 away win against Sampdoria.[151] He scored his first Serie A hat-trick on 6 January 2020, in a 4–0 home win against Cagliari and became only the second player to score hat-tricks in the Premier League, La Liga and Serie A.[152] On 22 February, Ronaldo scored for a record-equalling 11th consecutive league game, alongside Gabriel Batistuta and Fabio Quagliarella, in what was his 1,000th senior professional game, a 2–1 away win against SPAL.[153] On 22 June, he scored a penalty in a 2–0 away win over Bologna, overtaking Rui Costa to become the highest scoring Portuguese player in Serie A history.[154] On 20 July, Ronaldo scored twice in a 2–1 home win over Lazio; his first goal was his 50th in Serie A. He became the first player in history to reach 50 goals in the Premier League, La Liga and Serie A, and becoming the second player after Edin Džeko to score 50 goals in three of Europe\'s top five major leagues.[155] Moreover, he became the oldest player, at the age of 35 years and 166 days, to score over 30 goals in one of the five top European leagues since Ronnie Rooke with Arsenal in 1948.[156] On 26 July, Ronaldo scored the opening goal in a 2–0 home win over Sampdoria as Juventus were crowned Serie A champions for a ninth consecutive time.[157] On 7 August, Ronaldo scored a brace in a 2–1 home win against Lyon in the second leg of the Champions League round of 16, which saw him finish the season with 37 goals in all competitions; the tally allowed him to break Borel\'s club record of 36 goals in a single season.[158]\r\n\r\n2020–2021: 100 Juve goals, Capocannoniere, and departure\r\nRonaldo played his 100th match in all competitions for Juventus on 13 December, scoring two penalties in a 3–1 away win over Genoa in the league to bring his goal tally to 79.[159] On 2 March 2021, he scored a goal in a 3–0 win over Spezia in his 600th league match, to become the first player to score at least 20 goals in 12 consecutive seasons in the top five leagues of Europe.[160] On 12 May, Ronaldo scored a goal in a 3–1 away win over Sassuolo to reach his 100th goal for Juventus in all competitions on his 131st appearance, becoming the fastest Juventus player to achieve the feat.[161] With Juventus\'s victory in the 2021 Coppa Italia Final on 19 May, Ronaldo became the first player in history to win every major domestic trophy in England, Spain and Italy.[162] Ronaldo ended the season with 29 league goals, winning the Capocannoniere award for highest goalscorer and becoming the first footballer to finish as top scorer in the English, Spanish and Italian leagues.[163]\r\n\r\nThe start of the following season came amid reports Ronaldo would depart the club before the closure of the transfer window,[164] despite Ronaldo and his agent Jorge Mendes reaching a verbal agreement with Manchester City over personal terms,[165] but the club pulled out of the deal,[166] and later it was confirmed that City\'s rivals Manchester United, Ronaldo\'s former club, were in advanced talks to sign him,[167][168] while former manager Alex Ferguson and several ex-teammates had been in contact to persuade him to re-sign for United.[169][170]', '', 'text evaluation', '<h3>Evaluation of the Text on Cristiano Ronaldo</h3>\n<h4>Logical Organization and Flow of Ideas</h4>\n<p>The text exhibits a structured organization that outlines the life and career achievements of Cristiano Ronaldo. It begins with a comprehensive overview of his status in football, followed by a chronologically ordered account of his career milestones, international achievements, endorsements, and personal history.</p>\n<p>The flow is effective, moving seamlessly from his football beginnings through his time at various clubs, culminating with a brief mention of his early life. Each section effectively supports the narrative of Ronaldo’s evolution as a player. Transitions between paragraphs are appropriate, as they guide the reader from one stage of his career to another, allowing for coherent progression.</p>\n<p>However, suggestions for improvement could include using more explicit transition statements to connect the early life details to his club career explicitly, anchoring the narrative further—perhaps through a sentence that directly connects childhood experiences to his career motivations. Additionally, subtitles could enhance navigation through the text.</p>\n<h4>Clarity of Language, Word Choice, and Phrasing</h4>\n<p>The language employed in the text is generally clear and direct, providing extensive biographical details without overwhelming the reader with jargon. The word choice is predominantly precise, reflecting a formal and informative tone appropriate for a biography of a sports figure.</p>\n<p>That said, some complex sentence structures could be simplified to improve readability. For instance, the enumeration of awards and records could be broken down into bullet points or shorter sentences to avoid reader fatigue. Instances of vague terms—like “number of trophies” without specifying which or when—could be enhanced for clarity.</p>\n<h4>Tone Appropriateness</h4>\n<p>The tone is suitable for the intended audience, consisting of football fans and individuals interested in sports biographies. It maintains a respectful yet enthusiastic tone, celebrating Ronaldo’s achievements while providing factual information. The narrative instills a sense of admiration while remaining objective.</p>\n<p>However, a more engaging tone, perhaps integrating quotes from Ronaldo or different football pundits throughout the narrative rather than relegating them to summaries at the end of sections, could deepen emotional engagement with the reader. Adding personal anecdotes might also humanize the icon further and connect better with readers.</p>\n<h4>Reader Engagement Techniques</h4>\n<p>The text captures interest effectively through a narrative style that weaves personal achievements with contextual information regarding the football industry. This blend ensures the reader remains engaged, particularly with the extensive use of detailed statistics highlighting Ronaldo’s phenomenal skill set.</p>\n<p>To enhance engagement, the inclusion of more anecdotes or dramatic moments during his career could create a richer tapestry that invites greater emotional investment. Additionally, the use of direct quotes from teammates or coaches throughout his career could add an authentic touch and diversify the narrative\'s voice.</p>\n<h4>Originality and Creativity</h4>\n<p>The text primarily presents well-documented information about Cristiano Ronaldo’s life and career, which, while factually detailed, follows a conventional biographical format. It captures many standard elements pertaining to a sports legend’s life but does not diverge into more unique insights or perspectives.</p>\n<p>To enrich its originality, the text could benefit from a thematic exploration of a central motif throughout Ronaldo\'s career—such as resilience or ambition—that ties various achievements together more cohesively. Comparing his experiences with other great players in a contextual analysis could elevate the uniqueness of the narrative.</p>\n<h4>Depth of Topic Exploration</h4>\n<p>The text comprehensively spans numerous dimensions of Ronaldo’s career, including club performance, international records, and financial successes. However, while it lists many achievements, there is less focus on the implications of these accomplishments. </p>\n<p>More analysis regarding the impact of his legacy on football and how he compares with contemporaries in terms of playing style or cultural significance would add depth. Additionally, exploring his philanthropic efforts or personal views could round out the understanding of his character beyond football.</p>\n<h4>Grammar, Syntax, and Vocabulary</h4>\n<p>Overall, the grammar and syntax are solid, with well-constructed sentences that convey complex ideas clearly. The vocabulary is varied, enhancing the professional tone of the text.</p>\n<p>A few sentences exhibit excessive length and complexity, risking clarity. Breaking longer sentences into more digestible parts could aid comprehension. Additionally, occasional redundancy, such as repeating the \'number of titles\' figures, should be trimmed for conciseness.</p>\n<h4>Audience Tailoring</h4>\n<p>The text is appropriately tailored to a general audience interested in sports, maintaining a balance between detail and accessibility. However, to heighten its impact on a wider demographic, aspects such as wider cultural references or multimedia elements (if this were in a digital format) could enhance relatability for non-football fans.</p>\n<p>Implementing a glossary of football terms could also help less knowledgeable readers engage more fully with the content, ensuring the text\'s accessibility.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>In summary, the text encompasses a thorough account of Cristiano Ronaldo’s life, providing a detailed retrospective of his career. While it effectively conveys substantial informational content, incorporating improvements in structure, clarity, engagement techniques, and depth of exploration could enhance its overall quality. By refining some areas for reader navigability and emotional connection, the biography could resonate even more powerfully with its intended audience.</p>', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750fed69e8e68.67467050', '2024-12-04 18:16:06', '2024-12-04 18:16:06'),
(104, 9, 'Ngày xưa, có một ông già nhà quê có một cô gái đẹp. Trong nhà phải thuê một đầy tớ trai, ông ta muốn lợi dụng nó làm việc khỏi trả tiền, mới bảo nó rằng: “Mày chịu khó làm ăn với tao rồi tao gả con gái cho”. Người ở mừng lắm, ra sức làm lụng tới khuya không nề hà mệt nhọc. Nó giúp việc được ba năm, nhà ông ta mỗi ngày một giàu có.\r\n\r\nÔng nhà giàu không còn nghĩ đến lời hứa cũ nữa, đem con gái gả cho con một nhà phú hộ khác ở trong làng.\r\n\r\nSáng hôm sắp đưa dâu, ông chủ gọi đứa ở lên lừa nó một lần nữa, bảo rằng: “Bây giờ mày lên rừng tìm cho ra một cây tre có trăm đốt đem về đây làm đũa ăn cưới, thì tao cho mày lấy con gái tao ngay”.\r\n\r\nĐứa ở tưởng thật, vác dao đi rừng. Nó kiếm khắp nơi, hết rừng này qua rừng nọ, không tìm đâu thấy có cây tre đủ trăm đốt. Buồn khổ quá, nó ngồi một chỗ ôm mặt khóc. Bỗng thấy có một ông lão râu tóc bạc phơ, tay cầm gậy trúc hiện ra bảo nó: “Tại sao con khóc, hãy nói ta nghe, ta sẽ giúp cho”. Nó bèn đem đầu đuôi câu chuyện ông phú hộ hứa gả con gái cho mà kể lại. Ông lão nghe xong, mới bảo rằng: “Con đi chặt đếm đủ trăm cái đốt tre rồi đem lại đây ta bảo”.\r\n\r\nNó làm theo y lời dặn, ông dạy nó đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” (vào ngay, vào ngay) đủ ba lần, thì một trăm khúc tre tự nhiên dính lại với nhau thành một cây trẻ đủ một trăm đốt. Nó mừng quá, định vác về, nhưng cây tre dài quá, vướng không đi được. Ông lão bảo nó đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” (ra ngay, ra ngay) đúng ba lần thì cây tre trăm đốt lại rời ra ngay từng khúc.\r\n\r\nNó bèn bó cả lại mà gánh về nhà. Đến nơi thấy hai họ đang ăn uống vui vẻ, sắp đến lúc rước dâu, nó mới hay là ông chủ đã lừa nó đem gả con gái cho người ta rồi. Nó không nói gì, đợi lúc nhà trai đốt pháo cưới, bèn đem một trăm khúc tre xếp dài dưới đất, rồi lẩm bẩm đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” cho liền lại thành một cây tre trăm đốt, đoạn gọi ông chủ đến bảo là đã tìm ra được, và đòi gả con gái cho nó. Ông chủ lấy làm lạ cầm cây tre lên xem, nó đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì ông ta bị dính liền ngay vào cây tre, không làm sao gỡ ra được. Ông thông gia thấy vậy chạy đến, định gỡ cho, nó lại đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì cả ông cũng bị dính theo luôn, không lôi ra được nữa.\r\n\r\nHai họ thấy thế không còn ai dám lại gần nó nữa. Còn hai ông kia không còn biết làm thế nào đành van lạy xin nó thả ra cho. Ông chủ hứa gả con gái cho nó, ông thông gia xin về nhà ngay, nó để cho cả hai thề một hồi rồi nó mới đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” thì hai ông rời ngay cây tre, và cây tre cũng rời ra trăm khúc.', '<p>The text provided is a short folk tale rich in cultural context, moral values, and thematic depth, commonly found in various traditions, particularly in Vietnam. This analysis will explore its main ideas, structure, tone, style, language usage, and the various nuances embedded in the narrative.</p>\n<h3>Main Ideas and Underlying Meanings</h3>\n<p>At its core, the tale presents themes of deception, justice, and the triumph of the underdog. The story starts with an old farmer employing a young assistant, promising to reward him with his beautiful daughter in exchange for hard work. This promise serves as the initial motivation for the assistant, showcasing the hopes and aspirations of a downtrodden individual seeking a better life. However, the old farmer\'s betrayal—where he marries his daughter off to another man—highlights the deceptive nature of those with power over the less fortunate.</p>\n<p>The concept of the magical bamboo stick that can bind and release reflects the struggle for agency and the quest for justice. Through the apprentice\'s cleverness, he turns the tables on the old farmer and his new son-in-law, showcasing themes of wit, ingenuity, and retribution. Ultimately, it becomes a story of empowerment, illustrating how wisdom can outshine brute force or social inequity.</p>\n<h3>Organization and Flow</h3>\n<p>The narrative flows sequentially through a series of events that build tension and lead to the climax. Initially, the plot is set in motion with the introduction of the protagonist (the young servant) and his plight. The second part of the story involves a revelation of betrayal, which prompts the protagonist\'s quest to find the magic bamboo. The climax occurs when the protagonist uses the bamboo to entrap those who deceived him, and the resolution offers a return to equilibrium as he gains the promised reward.</p>\n<p>Each section fits cohesively, as the progression from labor, betrayal, the quest, and eventual justice aligns perfectly with traditional storytelling arcs. This structure effectively keeps the reader engaged, as it facilitates a natural buildup of anticipation and emotional involvement.</p>\n<h3>Tone and Style</h3>\n<p>The tone of the story fluctuates between serious and whimsical, which is characteristic of many folk tales. The initial serious tone reflects the hardship and exploitation faced by the protagonist. However, as the tale progresses, there is a more light-hearted and fanciful aspect introduced through the encounter with the old man and the magic bamboo. This tonal shift creates an engaging contrast, keeping the reader’s interest alive throughout the narrative.</p>\n<p>Stylistically, the tale employs simple yet vivid language that is accessible and relatable. The use of dialogue is crucial; it gives life to the characters and makes their interactions feel real. For example, the phrases “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” and “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” serve not only as magical incantations but also infuse the narrative with a rhythmic quality that reinforces the story’s folkloric nature.</p>\n<h3>Language Usage and Diction</h3>\n<p>The diction throughout the tale is straightforward, suitable for a wide audience, which is a hallmark of folklore intended for oral tradition. The choice of words is common and familiar, yet effective in painting a clear picture of the settings and characters. Phrases like &quot;mừng lắm&quot; (very happy) and &quot;buồn khổ quá&quot; (so sad) evoke strong emotional responses and help the reader to empathize with the characters.</p>\n<p>Imagery plays a subtle but significant role, particularly through the use of nature (the bamboo, forests) and elements that symbolize growth and potential. The bamboo itself serves as a powerful symbol, suggesting resilience, flexibility, and strength—qualities that the protagonist embodies as he navigates his challenges.</p>\n<h3>Sentence Patterns and Grammatical Techniques</h3>\n<p>The sentence constructions are predominantly simple and direct, making the story easy to follow. Regular use of dialogue interspersed with narrative description enhances the dynamism of the text. The use of repetition in the magic phrases effectively emphasizes their significance and creates a sense of rhythm, making the incantations memorable.</p>\n<p>Moreover, the tale employs contrast effectively, juxtaposing the humble beginnings of the servant with the privilege of the old farmer. This contrast not only helps to develop character backgrounds but also fosters a sense of empathy toward the protagonist\'s plight.</p>\n<h3>Multi-Dimensional Analysis</h3>\n<p>Delving deeper into the text reveals nuanced themes such as the exploitation inherent in master-servant relationships. The old farmer’s duplicity encapsulates the moral failings associated with power and greed. The eventual entrapment of both the farmer and the potential son-in-law signifies a poetic justice that resonates with readers, symbolizing that those who deceive others may ultimately fall victim to their own treachery.</p>\n<p>The underlying message also highlights the significance of cleverness and resourcefulness in overcoming adversity. The protagonist\'s journey underscores the importance of self-advocacy, as he does not remain passive in the face of betrayal but actively seeks the tools (both literal and metaphorical) to reclaim his destiny.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>In summary, this folk tale weaves together the threads of moral lessons, cultural identity, and human experience through its compelling narrative structure, engaging tone, and rich thematic layers. The portrayal of a clever underdog overcoming deceit fosters a sense of hope and resilience, resonating with audiences both young and old. Each element—be it language, structure, or character development—contributes to a deeply relatable story that transcends cultural boundaries, making it a timeless tale of justice and empowerment.</p>', 'text analysis', '', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750ff342dfc07.42642841', '2024-12-04 18:17:40', '2024-12-04 18:17:40');
INSERT INTO `text_analysis` (`id`, `user_id`, `text_content`, `analysis_result`, `type_of_analysis`, `evaluation`, `status`, `analysis_evaluation_code`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(105, 9, 'Ngày xưa, có một ông già nhà quê có một cô gái đẹp. Trong nhà phải thuê một đầy tớ trai, ông ta muốn lợi dụng nó làm việc khỏi trả tiền, mới bảo nó rằng: “Mày chịu khó làm ăn với tao rồi tao gả con gái cho”. Người ở mừng lắm, ra sức làm lụng tới khuya không nề hà mệt nhọc. Nó giúp việc được ba năm, nhà ông ta mỗi ngày một giàu có.\r\n\r\nÔng nhà giàu không còn nghĩ đến lời hứa cũ nữa, đem con gái gả cho con một nhà phú hộ khác ở trong làng.\r\n\r\nSáng hôm sắp đưa dâu, ông chủ gọi đứa ở lên lừa nó một lần nữa, bảo rằng: “Bây giờ mày lên rừng tìm cho ra một cây tre có trăm đốt đem về đây làm đũa ăn cưới, thì tao cho mày lấy con gái tao ngay”.\r\n\r\nĐứa ở tưởng thật, vác dao đi rừng. Nó kiếm khắp nơi, hết rừng này qua rừng nọ, không tìm đâu thấy có cây tre đủ trăm đốt. Buồn khổ quá, nó ngồi một chỗ ôm mặt khóc. Bỗng thấy có một ông lão râu tóc bạc phơ, tay cầm gậy trúc hiện ra bảo nó: “Tại sao con khóc, hãy nói ta nghe, ta sẽ giúp cho”. Nó bèn đem đầu đuôi câu chuyện ông phú hộ hứa gả con gái cho mà kể lại. Ông lão nghe xong, mới bảo rằng: “Con đi chặt đếm đủ trăm cái đốt tre rồi đem lại đây ta bảo”.\r\n\r\nNó làm theo y lời dặn, ông dạy nó đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” (vào ngay, vào ngay) đủ ba lần, thì một trăm khúc tre tự nhiên dính lại với nhau thành một cây trẻ đủ một trăm đốt. Nó mừng quá, định vác về, nhưng cây tre dài quá, vướng không đi được. Ông lão bảo nó đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” (ra ngay, ra ngay) đúng ba lần thì cây tre trăm đốt lại rời ra ngay từng khúc.\r\n\r\nNó bèn bó cả lại mà gánh về nhà. Đến nơi thấy hai họ đang ăn uống vui vẻ, sắp đến lúc rước dâu, nó mới hay là ông chủ đã lừa nó đem gả con gái cho người ta rồi. Nó không nói gì, đợi lúc nhà trai đốt pháo cưới, bèn đem một trăm khúc tre xếp dài dưới đất, rồi lẩm bẩm đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” cho liền lại thành một cây tre trăm đốt, đoạn gọi ông chủ đến bảo là đã tìm ra được, và đòi gả con gái cho nó. Ông chủ lấy làm lạ cầm cây tre lên xem, nó đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì ông ta bị dính liền ngay vào cây tre, không làm sao gỡ ra được. Ông thông gia thấy vậy chạy đến, định gỡ cho, nó lại đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì cả ông cũng bị dính theo luôn, không lôi ra được nữa.\r\n\r\nHai họ thấy thế không còn ai dám lại gần nó nữa. Còn hai ông kia không còn biết làm thế nào đành van lạy xin nó thả ra cho. Ông chủ hứa gả con gái cho nó, ông thông gia xin về nhà ngay, nó để cho cả hai thề một hồi rồi nó mới đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” thì hai ông rời ngay cây tre, và cây tre cũng rời ra trăm khúc.', '', 'text evaluation', '<p>The text presented is a traditional Vietnamese folk tale that demonstrates elements of moral lessons, betrayal, cleverness, and the consequences of deceit. Below is a detailed evaluation based on the specified criteria:</p>\n<h3>Logical Organization and Flow of Ideas</h3>\n<p>The narrative is structured in a clear chronological order, following a classic story arc that includes setup, conflict, and resolution. The introduction introduces the main characters and sets up the premise of the tale—the old man’s betrayal of the servant. The progression of events flows logically, as the servant tries to fulfill the impossible task set by his master, followed by the intervention of a magical character, leading to the climax and resolution.</p>\n<p>However, there is a slight lack of clarity in distinguishing between different phases of the story, especially when describing the magical transformation of the bamboo. Transition phrases could enhance coherence. While the action moves swiftly, adding brief transitional sentences could assist readers in following the narrative\'s progression more smoothly. Recommendations for improvement include implementing clearer demarcations between the servant\'s attempts, the magical intervention, and the climactic confrontation.</p>\n<h3>Clarity of Language and Word Choice</h3>\n<p>Language throughout the text is straightforward and largely clear, effectively conveying the story\'s intent. The use of phrases such as &quot;khắc nhập, khắc xuất&quot; provides an ethereal quality typical of folk tales while also contributing to the linguistic flavor. However, certain sections could benefit from elaboration or more precise terminology—particularly in describing the emotional state of the servant after realizing the betrayal. For example, instead of saying &quot;vừa khóc,&quot; a more descriptive emotional phrase could reinforce the servant\'s despair, thus enhancing the reader\'s connection.</p>\n<h3>Tone Appropriateness</h3>\n<p>The tone of the text aligns well with the folk tale genre—conversational yet imbued with an element of whimsy and moral lessons typical of traditional narratives. It maintains consistency throughout. However, a touch of dramatic irony could be amplified, particularly during the servant\'s realization of the master’s betrayal, to reinforce the emotional gravity of the moment. </p>\n<p>Alternative tones to consider might include a more mocking or sardonic tone, particularly in interactions with the affluent master, to emphasize moral implications further. Such a tone could enhance the satirical undercurrents present in many folk tales, where the wealthy are often depicted as foolish or morally bankrupt.</p>\n<h3>Reader Interest and Engagement</h3>\n<p>The narrative captures the reader\'s interest with its classic elements of a folk tale—deceit, magic, and resolution through cleverness. The unfolding of the plot, particularly the introduction of the old man with magic powers, adds an engaging twist. However, additional engagement techniques—such as more vivid imagery or a deeper exploration of character motivations—could strengthen reader investment. For instance, a deeper reflection on the servant\'s internal thoughts throughout the betrayal might enhance emotional resonance.</p>\n<h3>Originality and Creativity</h3>\n<p>While the tale follows a traditional pattern, the use of bamboo as a magical element and the unique incantation demonstrate creativity in execution. However, the overarching plot of the deceitful master and wrongly deprived servant is a conventional narrative in many cultures. The originality could be enhanced by introducing unexpected elements or twists that deviate from common folk tale tropes.</p>\n<h3>Depth of Exploration</h3>\n<p>The text explores its main themes effectively—betrayal, cleverness, and justice—against the backdrop of class disparity. However, it might benefit from further detailing the secondary characters, such as the old man\'s daughter and her feelings, which would add depth to the narrative. Including her perspective on the unfolding events could enrich the story and provide a more rounded exploration of the consequences of betrayal.</p>\n<h3>Grammar, Syntax, and Vocabulary Choices</h3>\n<p>Overall, the grammatical structure is solid, with clear syntactical organization that supports readability. Vietnamese language conventions are adhered to, reflecting traditional storytelling methods. While vocabulary is appropriate for the target audience, simpler alternatives for more complex phrases might improve accessibility for younger or less proficient readers.</p>\n<h3>Audience Tailoring</h3>\n<p>The text appears well-suited for its intended audience of children and families, typical of folk tales which often serve didactic purposes. The language complexity is appropriate, but incorporating more illustrative language that appeals to younger imaginations could significantly enhance engagement. Small adjustments such as adding questions for the reader, encouraging them to predict outcomes, could create a more interactive experience.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>This Vietnamese folk tale captures essential elements of traditional narratives, effectively conveying moral lessons through a combination of clarity, organization, and engagement techniques. Enhancements in transition clarity, emotional depth, and character exploration would elevate the text\'s overall impact, rendering it not only a tale of wit and consequence but also a richer narrative experience for all ages.</p>', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750ff458a96c6.90640086', '2024-12-04 18:17:57', '2024-12-04 18:17:57'),
(106, 9, 'Ngày xưa, có một ông già nhà quê có một cô gái đẹp. Trong nhà phải thuê một đầy tớ trai, ông ta muốn lợi dụng nó làm việc khỏi trả tiền, mới bảo nó rằng: “Mày chịu khó làm ăn với tao rồi tao gả con gái cho”. Người ở mừng lắm, ra sức làm lụng tới khuya không nề hà mệt nhọc. Nó giúp việc được ba năm, nhà ông ta mỗi ngày một giàu có.\r\n\r\nÔng nhà giàu không còn nghĩ đến lời hứa cũ nữa, đem con gái gả cho con một nhà phú hộ khác ở trong làng.\r\n\r\nSáng hôm sắp đưa dâu, ông chủ gọi đứa ở lên lừa nó một lần nữa, bảo rằng: “Bây giờ mày lên rừng tìm cho ra một cây tre có trăm đốt đem về đây làm đũa ăn cưới, thì tao cho mày lấy con gái tao ngay”.\r\n\r\nĐứa ở tưởng thật, vác dao đi rừng. Nó kiếm khắp nơi, hết rừng này qua rừng nọ, không tìm đâu thấy có cây tre đủ trăm đốt. Buồn khổ quá, nó ngồi một chỗ ôm mặt khóc. Bỗng thấy có một ông lão râu tóc bạc phơ, tay cầm gậy trúc hiện ra bảo nó: “Tại sao con khóc, hãy nói ta nghe, ta sẽ giúp cho”. Nó bèn đem đầu đuôi câu chuyện ông phú hộ hứa gả con gái cho mà kể lại. Ông lão nghe xong, mới bảo rằng: “Con đi chặt đếm đủ trăm cái đốt tre rồi đem lại đây ta bảo”.\r\n\r\nNó làm theo y lời dặn, ông dạy nó đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” (vào ngay, vào ngay) đủ ba lần, thì một trăm khúc tre tự nhiên dính lại với nhau thành một cây trẻ đủ một trăm đốt. Nó mừng quá, định vác về, nhưng cây tre dài quá, vướng không đi được. Ông lão bảo nó đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” (ra ngay, ra ngay) đúng ba lần thì cây tre trăm đốt lại rời ra ngay từng khúc.\r\n\r\nNó bèn bó cả lại mà gánh về nhà. Đến nơi thấy hai họ đang ăn uống vui vẻ, sắp đến lúc rước dâu, nó mới hay là ông chủ đã lừa nó đem gả con gái cho người ta rồi. Nó không nói gì, đợi lúc nhà trai đốt pháo cưới, bèn đem một trăm khúc tre xếp dài dưới đất, rồi lẩm bẩm đọc: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập” cho liền lại thành một cây tre trăm đốt, đoạn gọi ông chủ đến bảo là đã tìm ra được, và đòi gả con gái cho nó. Ông chủ lấy làm lạ cầm cây tre lên xem, nó đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì ông ta bị dính liền ngay vào cây tre, không làm sao gỡ ra được. Ông thông gia thấy vậy chạy đến, định gỡ cho, nó lại đọc luôn: “Khắc nhập, khắc nhập”, thì cả ông cũng bị dính theo luôn, không lôi ra được nữa.\r\n\r\nHai họ thấy thế không còn ai dám lại gần nó nữa. Còn hai ông kia không còn biết làm thế nào đành van lạy xin nó thả ra cho. Ông chủ hứa gả con gái cho nó, ông thông gia xin về nhà ngay, nó để cho cả hai thề một hồi rồi nó mới đọc: “Khắc xuất, khắc xuất” thì hai ông rời ngay cây tre, và cây tre cũng rời ra trăm khúc.', '<p>The provided text is a traditional Vietnamese folktale that encapsulates themes of deception, justice, and the cleverness of the underdog. Within this narrative, each element—be it the characters, plot structure, choice of language, and cultural allusions—serves to paint a vivid picture of rural life, social hierarchies, and moral lessons that resonate deeply within the cultural context.</p>\n<h3>Main Ideas and Underlying Meanings</h3>\n<p>At its core, the tale revolves around the exploitation of the servant by the wealthy old man, highlighting themes of inequality and betrayal. The aged farmer initially offers the servant a false promise of marriage to his daughter in exchange for hard labor, which positions the servant as a figure who is both hopeful and naive. This dynamic sets the stage for a classic tale of justice, where the servant is ultimately wronged yet finds a way to reclaim dignity.</p>\n<p>The narrative arc leads us through the servant’s desperate quest to fulfill an impossible task—finding and retrieving a bamboo with a hundred nodes—only to meet a wise old man who aids him. This introduces the theme of mentorship and the idea that wisdom often lies in the unexpected. The old man’s guidance repurposes the challenge into an opportunity, emphasizing the importance of knowledge and cleverness over brute labor. </p>\n<p>The tale culminates in a moment of poetic justice where the servant, armed with magical incantations, traps both the master and the prospective father-in-law in a bamboo stick, forcing them to confess to their wrongdoings and promise the original pact of marriage. This sequence exemplifies not just a reversal of power dynamics but also a clever negotiation of social contracts—one where the oppressed agent becomes empowered through wit.</p>\n<h3>Organization and Flow</h3>\n<p>The structure of the narrative follows a clear progression: introduction, rising action, climax, and resolution. Initially, we meet the main characters—the old man and the servant—and understand the basis of their relationship through the promise of marriage. The rising action escalates with the servant\'s excursions into the forest, emphasizing his plight. </p>\n<p>As the servant receives help from the old man, the tension builds toward the climax where the servant cleverly employs the magic he has learned. The narrative flow from despair to empowerment is seamless, enhancing the readers\' engagement with the unfolding drama. The rapid shift in power dynamics captures the reader\'s attention and effectively drives home the idea that justice will be served.</p>\n<h3>Language and Diction</h3>\n<p>The text employs simple yet evocative language characteristic of folktales, blending oral storytelling elements with a rhythmic quality that resonates with listeners and readers alike. Phrases like “Khắc nhập, khắc xuất” are not only magical formulas but also serve to create an incantatory feel that reinforces the element of magic in the tale. </p>\n<p>Moreover, the imagery of the bamboo—strong yet flexible—can be interpreted symbolically; it represents resilience and resourcefulness. This choice of imagery underscores cultural values surrounding nature and the significance of natural elements within Vietnamese folk narratives.</p>\n<p>The diction employed throughout the story alternates between straightforward narrative descriptions and moments of vivid interactive dialogue, notably in scenes involving the servant\'s conversations with the old man and the ultimate confrontation involving the bamboo stick. The use of traditional idiomatic expressions caters to cultural familiarity, anchoring the tale firmly within its Vietnamese origins.</p>\n<h3>Sentence Patterns and Grammatical Techniques</h3>\n<p>The narrative utilizes a blend of simple and compound sentences that maintain clarity while allowing for detailed storytelling. The repetitive use of commands, such as “Khắc nhập, khắc xuất,” creates a rhythm that mirrors the incantational aspect of the text while highlighting the protagonist\'s agency. </p>\n<p>Additionally, the use of direct speech throughout enables characters\' motivations and emotions to be directly transmitted to the reader, thus making their personalities more relatable and their conflicts more immediate. This attention to dialogue enriches character development, particularly that of the old man who acts as a significant transitional figure in the servant\'s journey.</p>\n<h3>Themes and Subtexts</h3>\n<p>Several nuanced themes permeate the narrative, including the idea of loyalty versus betrayal, the wisdom of experience over the ignorance of youth, and the possibility of upward mobility through intelligence rather than wealth. The implicit message encourages the audience to recognize that true power often lies not in might but in collaboration, foresight, and clever maneuvering.</p>\n<p>The tale also speaks to the socio-economic realities of the time, reflecting the intricate relationships between the rich and the poor within Vietnamese society. The servant\'s experience echoes broader societal commentaries regarding class struggles while simultaneously celebrating the triumph of the disenfranchised through resourcefulness.</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>In conclusion, this folktale encapsulates timeless lessons in justice, cleverness, and social dynamics through its engaging plot and characterizations. The intricate details—the circular structure of the narrative, the cultural richness of the language, the symbolic imagery, and the underlying social commentary—serve to create a robust text that invites readers to reflect on larger themes of fairness and the complexity of human relationships. The servant’s eventual triumph offers a narrative of hope and resilience, which resonates deeply across cultures and time, making it a compelling addition to the canon of moral storytelling within Vietnamese folklore.</p>', 'text analysis', '', 'completed', 'wordifyai_6750ffd83482b3.21655459', '2024-12-04 18:20:24', '2024-12-04 18:20:24'),
